<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian King Meets U.S. Commander on Military Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein
on Wednesday met with visiting Commander-in-Chief of the U.S.
Central Command Gen. Tommy Franks for discussions on military
cooperation between the countries.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Abdullah appreciated U.S. assistance to
Jordan's armed forces in defense and training fields, and
attributed such aid to the close friendly ties between the two
countries, Jordan's official news agency Petra reported.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was also attended by Jordanian Royal Court Chief
Fayez Tarawneh, Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff Mohammad
Yousef Malkawi and U.S. Ambassador to Jordan William Burns, Petra
said.
</P>
<P>
Franks is the highest U.S. military official to visit Jordan
this year to assess the defense needs of the kingdom, which
Washington takes as an ally in the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is also Jordan's major supplier of arms and military
equipment, including fighter and military transport planes, radars,
missiles, rifles, tanks and armoured vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government provided over 300 million U.S. dollars in
various aid packages to Jordan in 1999, including 46.5 million
dollars in military financing and training programs.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is the largest recipient of U.S. assistance on per capita
basis, with Washington having given it over 2.4 billion dollars in
economic and military aid during the past decade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
