<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudanese, Eritrean Defense Ministers Meet to Ease Tension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese Defense Minister Bakri
Hassan Saleh held talks with his Eritrean counterpart Sebhat Ephrem
here Wednesday on easing tension between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The meeting focused on ways of improving the tense bilateral
relations and removing all obstacles between the two sides,
according to the Sudanese News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The two sides expressed their desire to enhance and strengthen
the bilateral ties in line with the instructions of their leaders
to serve the common interests of their people and preserve peace
and stability in the region, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
They will continue the talks on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Eritrean minister arrived here at mid-day Wednesday on an
official visit, during which he will convey a message from Eritrean
President Issayas Aferwerki to Sudanese President Omar el-Bashir.
</P>
<P>
"This visit will pave the way for the continuation of dialog on
major issues between the two countries especially security," Ephrem
told reporters upon his arrival here.
</P>
<P>
On July 20 Saleh visited Asmara, capital of Eritrea, to discuss
with Ephrem the reported Eritrean military support for Sudanese
rebels.
</P>
<P>
The Eritrean minister said his country did not harbor any
animosity against Sudan. "There is no Eritrean military build-up on
the borders with Sudan and all press reports on the issue are
groundless," Ephrem noted.
</P>
<P>
"Eritrea does not intend to invade Sudan," he said.
</P>
<P>
In July, governor of Sudanese eastern province of Kassala
Ibrahim Mahmoud Hamid accused Eritrea of backing a military
offensive the Sudanese rebels were planning to launch on the
eastern borders.
</P>
<P>
The tension reached its peak in May when Eritrea accused Sudan
of allowing the Ethiopian forces to cross its territory in order to
attack West Eritrea during the Eritrean-Ethiopian conflict.
</P>
</TEXT>
