<HEADLINE> Egypt Foils Attempt to Smuggle Rare Antiquities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Egypt on Wednesday foiled an attempt
by a furniture dealer to smuggle rare antiquities to the United
States, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The dealer, identified as Taha Ghanem, was arrested at
Alexandria port on the Mediterranean coast while trying to smuggle
the antiquities, which were estimated to be worth 30 million
Egyptian
pounds (8.7 million U.S. dollars), Egypt's official news agency
said.
</P>
<P>
The antiquities, which date back to various historical periods
from Greco-Roman times to the Egyptian monarchy of the 20th
century, were discovered hidden in a shipment of furniture, police
officials told the agency.
</P>
<P>
The police confiscated the pieces, including a column from a
Greek temple, 10 wooden chairs inlaid with ivory and mother-of-
pearl and portraits of two of the country's last kings, Farouk and
Fuad, in gold frames as well as copper pots, Chinese vases and a
stash of silverware, which the dealer confessed were collected in
the past three years.
</P>
<P>
Investigations showed that the arrested man had a deal with a
company in Houston to smuggle antiquities from various periods to
the U.S., the officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
