<DOCNO> XIE20000802.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Urged to Promote Use of Unleaded Fuel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 2 (Xinhua) -- An environmental group of the
United Arab Emirates has called for a hike in the price of leaded
fuel to make environment-friendly unleaded fuel more attractive to
motorists.
</P>
<P>
This demand is a response to a statement recently issued by
retailers that they are losing almost 1.40 dirhams (about 0.38 U.S.
dollars) on every gallon of fuel they sell because of the rising
price of crude oil on the international market, reported the local
media on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Habiba Al Marashi, chairman of the Emirates Environmental Group,
said this gap could be closed by increasing the price of leaded
fuel.
</P>
<P>
"Now is the time to act and kill two birds with one stone," Al
Marashi said, adding, "If they want to increase the price, then do
it on leaded fuel and leave the unleaded alone."
</P>
<P>
"I have always felt the government should step in and subsidize
unleaded fuel, but this will not be necessary if the price of
leaded is increased above it," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) has issued a directive,
saying all imported cars in the member states must be able to run
on unleaded fuel by the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
Al Marashi noted that it is time to change the price now in
order to speed the transition, saying that if the price of unleaded
is made cheaper than leaded, then more people will start using it
and they will be accustomed to it before this rule comes into
effect.
</P>
<P>
By last year, 36 countries in North America, Europe, East Asia
and South America had switched to unleaded fuel. Nine more are
switching this year, and another 20 are expected to do so by 2005.
</P>
<P>
Qatar led the way in the GCC member states, introducing unleaded
fuel in 1984. It became fully unleaded last June 1.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia is the only GCC country which doesn't offer
unleaded fuel at its petrol stations, but has pledged to do so by
the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
Emissions from leaded petrol are known to cause environmental
pollution and have prompted a myriad of health and safety concerns.
</P>
<P>
The six-member GCC also include Bahrain, Kuwait and Oman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
