<DOCNO> XIE20000802.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Breakthrough Unexpected in Third Round of Cyprus Talks: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus government spokesman
Michalis Papapetrou Wednesday expressed doubt over whether
breakthrough can be made on the Cyprus issue by the end of the
current phase of Cyprus peace talks in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on reported remarks by U.S. envoy Alfred Moses on
possible breakthrough in certain issues of the Cyprus problem,
Papapetrou said "it would be utopian to expect that there can be a
full break in the impasse in the next few days by the end of this
phase of talks."
</P>
<P>
Papapetrou, speaking in Geneva, said the Cyprus government
welcomes any breakthrough in the peace talks but so far there is no
indication that this could be achieved.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities since 1974 when Turkey invaded and occupied the
northern third of the island after a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Two rounds of U.N.-sponsored proximity talks, during which
Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash talked in an indirect way through United Nations officials
shuffling between them, have already been held since December 1999.
</P>
<P>
However, no substantive achievements have been made so far.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots insist that they will not hold direct talks
with the Greek Cypriot-dominated government unless their breakaway
regime in northern Cyprus, declared in 1983 and recognized only by
Turkey, gets international recognition and talks with the
government on parallel basis.
</P>
<P>
The third round, which is underway in Geneva, will end on Friday
and a fourth round is scheduled for September in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Papapetrou said the Cyprus government wishes to see something
substantive emerging from the talks by October and aims at
clinching a deal at any time.
</P>
<P>
He refrained from further comment because of the news blackout
the U.N. has imposed.
</P>
<P>
According to Cyprus News Agency, U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan's special adviser for Cyprus Alvaro de Soto on Wednesday held
separate meetings with Clerides and Denktash.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after his meeting with de Soto, Clerides said that "
good work was done," adding that "I am happy that we are talking."
</P>
<P>
"Everything is going on fine," said Denktash after his meeting
with de Soto. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
