<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Prices Slowdown In UK Eases Rate Pressure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 2 (Xinhua) - Property prices in the UK fell
during July, according to the latest monthly update from the
Nationwide, one of the largest building societies in Britain.
</P>
<P>
It said house prices fell 0.2 percent in July to stand 13.9
percent higher than a year ago. This compares with a rise of 0.4
percent in the month of June and an annual rise of 15.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Nationwide director David Parry said that on a regional basis
it appeared that prices in London had seen the most significant
slowdown.
</P>
<P>
"Part of the explanation for the weakening is that price rises
over the last twelve months were simply not sustainable and fewer
first time buyers are entering the market," Parry said.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown in house prices could ease the dilemma facing the
Bank of England on the eve of its monthly review of interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) gets together Wednesday for
the start of what has been described as the most difficult meeting
to predict in its three-year history.
</P>
<P>
Since the MPC has expressed concern in the past that rising
house prices may bolster consumer expenditure, as homeowners feel
more wealthy and are encouraged to spend, it will take comfort
from the latest data.
</P>
<P>
However, Parry said "although the housing market is reining
back the excessive growth of last year, with the economy strong
this could merely be a pause for breath." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
