<HEADLINE> Two Militiamen Killed in Shoot-out With U.N. Troops in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 2 (Xinhua) -- For the first time, two
militia men were killed Wednesday by the United Nations
peacekeeping forces in East Timor in Maliana District, some 10
kilometers from the border of West Timor, Indonesia, the United
Nations said.
</P>
<P>
According to U.N. spokesman Manoel de Almeida e Silva,
peacekeepers from the Australian Battalion had been tracking
militia activity in Maliana District based on information given by
Timorese who live in the area since the day before.
</P>
<P>
"Shortly after noon today, they came across a group of four to
five militia, who were armed with rifles and grenades, and they
shot and killed tow militia members, while the others are still at
large," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
No U.N. peacekeepers were injured in the incident, he said.
</P>
<P>
In Dili, the head of the United Nations Transitional
Administration in East Timor, Sergio Vieira de Mello, said that
the incident was important because "it indicates that the militia
remain active."
</P>
<P>
De Mello added that the rules of engagement in East Timor had
not changed, but were being applied at the border "without the
lightest hesitation."
</P>
<P>
The Force Commander of the U.N. forces, Lieutenant General
Boonsrang Niumpradit, said that today's events should "send a
signal across the border to make militia members think twice
before placing human lives in jeopardy." 
</P>
</TEXT>
