<HEADLINE> Profits Defy sales Slip At World Giant Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 2 (Xinhua) - World drugs giant AstraZeneca has
posted better-than-expected first-half year profits of 2.1 billion
US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Despite having to overcome a slowdown in sales of its block-
buster ulcer treatment Losec, pretax profits rose 17 percent in
the six months to June 30, according to its interim result report.
</P>
<P>
Sales of Losec, the world's best-selling drug, rose 7 percent
to 3 billion US dollars in the first half but the figures masked a
one-percent decline during the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
Chief executive of the Anglo-Swedish giant Tom McKillop said
the company's five main drugs, which include its anti-heart
disease drug Atacand and its Zomig migraine treatment, had "
contributed strongly" to profit growth.
</P>
<P>
AstraZeneca earnings per share came in at 96 cents against 83
cents a year ago and the company is to pay a 23 cents half-year
dividend, unchanged from a year ago as expected.
</P>
<P>
The company also said merger cost savings had exceeded
expectation, at 282.7 million US dollars. 
</P>
