<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Barak Faces Tough Political Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Qi Deliang
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Shortly after Foreign Minister
David Levy resigned on Wednesday from the government of Prime
Minister Ehud Barak, Israel's Knesset (parliament) passed in its
preliminary reading an opposition bill asking for early elections.
</P>
<P>
In an announcement at his office inside the Knesset, Levy said
he can not accept Barak's peace policies, accusing Barak of making
too many concessions to the Palestinians at the Camp David summit,
particularly on the Jerusalem issue.
</P>
<P>
He also criticized the prime minister for the "complete failure
in the areas of education and welfare."
</P>
<P>
After announcing his resignation, Levy carried out the second
part of his threat, voting for dissolving the Knesset and holding
early elections.
</P>
<P>
Levy's resignation has dealt another political blow to Barak by
reducing the now 12-member cabinet to an absolute minority of 40
seats in the 120-member Knesset. Under such circumstances, it is
hard for the government even to run the daily business and get its
bills pass through the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
Barak said he respected Levy's decision and that the resignation
will not affect his efforts to continue the peace process with the
Palestinians and to carry out necessary changes for strengthening
the future of Israel.
</P>
<P>
The opposition's early election bill has to pass another three
readings before turning into law.
</P>
<P>
The Knesset will start its three-month recess Wednesday evening.
During this period, no special Knesset session will be held unless
at least 61 members support such a request. Therefore, Barak has
three months to clean the political mess at home.
</P>
<P>
Barak said he intended first of all to form a new coalition
government with previous partners such as Shas and Meretz party,
which have jumped off the boat.
</P>
<P>
But the problem is that Shas will not support the peace
agreement with the Palestinians and the government would collapse
again if Shas leave the coalition when the peace deal is reached.
</P>
<P>
The second option for Barak is to form a national unity
government with the rightist Likud, as Levy and Yisrael Ba'aliya
leader Natan Sharansky asked for. But this coalition could hinder
his efforts toward reaching the peace agreement with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Sharansky has already suggested that Likud leader Ariel Sharon
and Barak devise principles for establishing a national unity
government by revising all the proposals and understandings raised
and discussed at Camp David summit.
</P>
<P>
The third option for Barak is to strike a peace deal with the
Palestinian within three months. This agreement would receive no
majority support in the Knesset, and then Barak would call for
elections to let the people decide whether they accept the deal nor
not. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
