<HEADLINE> Egyptian Government Urged to Set Date for Bar Association Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian Administrative Court on
Wednesday demanded that the government set a date for the elections
of the Bar Association board members.
</P>
<P>
Ali Shahata, a judge of the court, overturned a decision made by
the government on July 1 to indefinitely postpone the vote, and
ruled that the legal committee for supervising the elections must
fix a new date, the country's official Middle East News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The court ruling came after a lawsuit filed by opposition lawyer
Ahmed Nasser, who was a candidate for the 25-member board of the
association, and two other lawyers demanding a date to be fixed.
</P>
<P>
It would be the first election since the government froze the
Bar's activities in January 1996 on allegations of bad financial
management.
</P>
<P>
Analysts in Cairo have said the freeze and delay of elections
were aimed at preventing the fundamentalist Muslim Brotherhood from
controlling the Bar Association. In the last board, 16 of its 25
seats were held by Brotherhood members.
</P>
<P>
The Muslim Brotherhood, which was banned in the 1950s, is
generally tolerated by the government as it advocates an Islamic
state by peaceful means. 
</P>
