<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Accuses Tobacco Firms of Undermining Battle Against Smoking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization (WHO)
has accused cigarette manufacturers of trying to sabotage its
efforts to combat smoking.
</P>
<P>
Releasing a report entitled Tobacco Company Strategies to
Undermine Tobacco Control Activities at the World Health
Organization here Wednesday, WHO spokesman David Nabarro said that
the report was particularly worrying because "it suggests that a
small number of companies have attempted to subvert the process by
which the WHO is run".
</P>
<P>
In the report compiled by a WHO panel of experts, led by
Director of the Swiss Public Health Office Thomas Zeltner,
concluded that tobacco companies had engaged in "systematic
efforts" to "undermine and subvert" the WHO's anti-smoking
campaign.
</P>
<P>
The report is likely to provide the WHO with useful ammunition
in its attempts to persuade countries to sign up to the world's
first international treaty to curb smoking and ban cigarette
advertising.
</P>
<P>
The report states that "the attempted subversion had been
elaborate, well-financed, sophisticated and usually invisible". It
alleges that cigarette manufacturers tried to cut its budget, pit
other United Nations agencies against it, and distort results of
important scientific studies on tobacco.
</P>
<P>
Much of the information contained in the report comes from
tobacco company documents, which were made public after lawsuits
against the firms in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Derek Yach of WHO's anti-tobacco initiative, was quoted as
saying that the agency was shocked that "so much of this work was
done under cover. The scale of the intensity and the volume of all
these activities are really disturbing".
</P>
<P>
In a specific case, the WHO report alleged that top executives
from the tobacco giant, Philip Morris, had devised a plan to
contain, neutralize and reorient" the agency's anti-tobacco
initiatives, at a secret meeting in Boca Raton, Florida, in 1988.
</P>
<P>
The WHO claims that many of the tactics agreed at this meeting
were still being implemented. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000802.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Earns Another 387 Million Dollars in U.N."Oil-for-Food" Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Iraq exported some 387
million U.S. dollars worth of oil last week, the latest figures
from the United Nations Office of Iraq Program said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Office, which administers the U.N. humanitarian "oil-for-
food" program, reported that humanitarian supplies and equipment
for Iraq's oil industry continued to arrive normally during the
period from July 22 to 28.
</P>
<P>
Food deliveries included wheat, cooking oil, sugar and tea, and
a range of pharmaceutical products was also delivered , along with
detergents, tractors, herbicides, fertilizers, a refrigeration van,
a firefighting vehicle, classroom furniture, sanitation equipment
and other supplies, the Office said.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the United Nations Security Council sanctions
committee monitoring the sanctions against Iraq approved six new
contracts for the sale of oil, bringing the total number of
approved contracts to 86, with a volume of over 353 million
barrels at market value, the Office said.
</P>
<P>
Under the Security Council resolution establishing the oil-for-
food program, 66 percent of earning goes to fund the country's
humanitarian needs and 30 percent is directed to the Compensation
Commission which pays claims arising from Iraq's 1990 invasion of
Kuwait. The remainder goes to pay the costs of the U.N. Monitoring
Verification and Inspection Commission and U.N. operational costs.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions against Iraq cannot be lifted until the United
Nations clarifies that Iraq has destroyed all its weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. arm inspectors have been away from Iraq since the U.S.
-led military air strikes against the country in December 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000802.0034 </DOCNO>
