<HEADLINE> U.N. to Send Experts to Probe Illicit Diamonds Trade in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNTIED NATIONS, August 2 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Wednesday confirmed the composition of a five-member
panel of experts to look anew into the link between the diamonds
trade and the fighting in Sierra Leone, a U.N. spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Manoel de Almeida e Silva, the U.N. spokesman, told a press
conference that the confirmation was contained in Annan's letter
to the president of the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The chairman of the U.N. Security Council Sanctions Committee
on Sierra Leone, Anwarul Chowdhury who is the permanent
representative of Bangladesh to the United Nations, announced at
the press conference here Tuesday that the panel will be headed by
Martin Chungong Ayafor of Cameroon and the other four members are
from Belgium, Canada, India and Senegal.
</P>
<P>
Other members are Ian Smillie, a diamond expert from Canada,
Johan Peleman, an expert on arms and transportation from Belgium,
Harjit Singh Sandhu, an expert from Interpol and an Indian
national, and Atabou Bodian, an expert from the International
Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) and a national of Senegal.
</P>
<P>
Diamonds are at the heart of tragedy in Sierra Leone, where a
thriving gems-for-guns business fan the hard-to-end warfare.
</P>
<P>
The panel will report back to the sanctions committee by the
end of October, the chairman said.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions committee is similar to one that looked into
conflict involving Angola's UNITA rebels and concluded a report
last May.
</P>
<P>
Chowdhury said his own committee would fully probe allegations
leveled Monday by U.S. and British diplomats that Burkina Faso and
Liberia were fueling Sierra Leone's civil war and profiting from
its accompanying trade in arms and diamonds.
</P>
<P>
The panel composition was announced at the end of the two-day
public hearing on illicit diamonds trade in Sierra Leone, which,
the first of its kind, were requested by a July 5 Security Council
resolution imposing an global embargo on diamonds exports from the
West African country for at least 18 months unless the gems are
certified by the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
