<DOCNO> XIE20000802.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Leading Economic Indicators Unchanged in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The Composite Index of Leading
Economic Indicators in the United States was unchanged in June,
indicating that the nation's economy is cooling, The Conference
Board said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Conference Board, a prominent business research group, said
in a survey that the leading index remains at 106.00 in June,
after a 0.1 percent decline in May and no change in April.
</P>
<P>
"The leading indicators are cooling off from the rapid pace
registered at the end of last year," said Conference Board
Economist Ken Goldstein. "This is not the kind of performance to
be expected when Gross Domestic Product grows by 5.2 percent, as
it did in the second quarter of 2000."
</P>
<P>
Goldstein said some unusual influences are having an impact on
the leading indicators, especially the interplay between the bond
market and the Federal Reserve Board.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve has raised interest rates six times since
June last year in an effort to cool off the U.S. economy. The
latest number of the leading index may have a role in a decision
about whether the Central Bank will raise rates again at the
August 22 meeting.
</P>
<P>
The stronger-than-expected economic growth in the second
quarter, which runs against other indicators that showed the
slowing economy after six rate hikes, sparked fears of more rate
hikes.
</P>
<P>
The Conference Board said the flat pace in the leading
indicators in the recent months clearly pointed to moderating
momentum in the pace of economic activity. Among the ten
indicators that make up the leading index, only four rose in June.
</P>
<P>
The index, an important gauge of the U.S. economic activity for
next three to six months, stood at 100 in 1996, its base year.
</P>
</TEXT>
