<HEADLINE> Irish PM Says Won't Free IRA Killers of Policeman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"The position is as it's always been. There's been no change in
the circumstances," a Reuters report monitored here quoted Ahern
as saying in Dublin, the Irish capital.
</P>
<P>
Ahern made the comment shortly after Sinn Fein, the political
ally of IRA, is arguing that the four should be freed as part of
an early release scheme for paramilitary prisoners caught up in
Northern Ireland's bloody conflict.
</P>
<P>
The Irish prime minister is standing firm on his refusal to
free the killers of police detective Jerry McCabe in what is a
highly emotive case in the Irish Republic.
</P>
<P>
He brushed off speculation of a legal challenge to try to
secure the release of the IRA men, saying it would be dealt with
if and when it happened.
</P>
<P>
A Dublin court in 1999 sentenced the four people into prison
after they pleaded guilty to the manslaughter of McCabe.
</P>
<P>
McCabe was shot dead while escorting a postal van carrying 81,
000 Irish pounds (about 94,350 United States dollars) in the
western Irish town of Adare in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The four killers in military fatigues jumped out of a jeep
which had rammed McCabe's police car. One fired a burst of shots
into the car without warning. Three shots hit McCabe, who died
minutes later.
</P>
<P>
Last week, British police released a number of guerrillas, in a
bid to bolster Northern Ireland's peace drive.
</P>
<P>
The early release scheme applied to guerrillas belonging to
groups on ceasefire and supporting the landmark 1998 Good Friday
peace accord. 
</P>
</TEXT>
