<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Strongly Deplores Violence in Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 2 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Wednesday strongly deplored the violence in Kashmir
and urged for maximum restraint to prevent any further escalation.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the spokesman's office said " The
Secretary-General has learned with great dismay about the series
of overnight massacres in Kashmir in which reportedly 93 people,
mostly Hindu pilgrims and other civilians, have been killed."
</P>
<P>
"He strongly deplores this violence and calls for maximum
restraint to prevent any further escalation," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"He reiterates his call for an end to terrorist attacks
wherever they may occur," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief once again urged India and Pakistan to find an
early political solution to the Kashmir problem.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here, a wave of violence that
began Tuesday evening with an attack by suspected Islamic
guerrillas left more then 90 people dead in less than in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
In the first and worst attack, gunmen opened fire on unarmed
Hindu pilgrims and Muslim porters on their way to a revered
religious shrine near Pahalgam, 55 miles south of Kashmir's
summer capital, Srinagar.  
</P>
