<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia to Raise Export Duties on Gasoline, Diesel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Russia will increase the export
duties on gasoline and diesel fuel to 25 euros per ton as of
September 15, Deputy Prime Minister Viktor Khristenko said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The resolution on the increase has been drafted and the new
duties will take effect one month after Prime Minister Mikhail
Kasyanov signs the resolution, the Interfax news agency quoted
Khristenko as saying following a meeting of the commission on
trade and tariff policy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Khristenko said the government would not modify its
basis for monitoring crude oil prices and therefore the export
duty on crude oil will continue to be calculated based on the
price of Urals crude. Khristenko had said earlier that Brent crude
might be used to monitor prices.
</P>
<P>
The export duties on gasoline and diesel are being increased in
order to ensure adequate supplies on the domestic market. Exports
of those products are now so lucrative that a shortage could
result, he said.
</P>
<P>
Khristenko said the higher export duties will generate 20
million U.S. dollars a month in supplementary revenues for the
federal budget.
</P>
<P>
The current export duty is 20 euros a ton for gasoline and 15
euro a ton for diesel, Interfax said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
