<DOCNO> XIE20000802.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. New Home Sales Fall in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Sales of new homes in the
United States fell 3.7 percent in June to a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of 829,000 units, the lowest level in more than two
years as rising mortgage rates sapped home demands, the Commerce
Department reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The June decline was the third straight monthly drop in new
home sales, pushing the seasonally adjusted annual sales rate down
to the lowest since December 1997.
</P>
<P>
New home sales had fallen 0.9 percent in May and were off 8.2
percent in April, reflecting the impact of the Federal Reserve's
campaign to push interest rates higher in an effort to slow the
economy. Year-on-year, new home sales in June were down 12.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
Mortgage rates hit a five-year high of 8.64 percent in mid-May,
although they have been dropping a bit in recent weeks. Last week,
the nationwide average for 30-year mortgages was 8.13 percent.
</P>
<P>
The decline in home sales pushed the price of new homes down in
June.
</P>
<P>
The median sales price, the midpoint where half the homes sold
for more and half for less, dropped 1.4 percent to 159,000 U.S.
dollars in June, down from 161,200 dollars in May. That was the
lowest median sales price since August 1999, when it was 154,900
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The average price of a new home sold in June was 196,300
dollars, down 1 percent from a May average of 198,300 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Sales were down in every region of the country in June except
the West, where they posted a 0.5 percent increase to an annual
sales rate of 220,000 units.
</P>
<P>
Sales fell the most in the Midwest, down 7 percent to a rate of
133,000 units, the slowest sales pace since September 1997. Sales
were off 5.1 percent in the South to an annual rate of 408,000
units and dropped 1.5 percent in the Northeast to an annual rate
of 67,000 units. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
