<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepalese PM Invites Indian Industry to Set Up Base in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Nepalese Prime Minister Girija
Prasad Koirala said here on Wednesday that the Indo-Nepal Trade
Treaty reflected India's understanding of Nepal's need to increase
exports and invited Indian industry to take advantage of the
treaty to set up production bases in the Himalayan kingdom.
</P>
<P>
"The Nepal-India Trade Treaty is guided by the principle of
mutual benefit and reflects India's understanding of Nepal's need
to increase exports through increased investments and expansion of
production base," Koirala was quoted by the Press Trust of India (
PTI) as saying in his address to the Confederation of Indian
Industry.
</P>
<P>
Koirala, who arrived here on Monday evening on a week-long
official visit, described his visit as a confidence-building
measure, said the PTI.
</P>
<P>
India-Nepal ties came under strain following the hijacking of
an Indian Airlines aircraft from Kathmandu to Afghanistan on
December 24 last year.
</P>
<P>
The trade treaty had given shape to a long-term mutually
beneficial economic cooperation between the two countries, Koirala
noted.
</P>
<P>
He assured Indian investors that Kathmandu would offer all
support and facilities to Indian subsidiaries in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
The Nepalese prime minister and his delegation continued to
hold "intensive parleys" with Indian leaders and officials on
Wednesday, during which both countries reiterated their
determination to work closely to fight terrorism, a senior
official with India's External Affairs Ministry was quoted as
saying by the PTI.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have also agreed to expedite the process of
border delineation and India has responded favorably to Nepal's
plea for a waiver of special additional customs duty of four
percent imposed by it on Nepalese goods, the official added.
</P>
<P>
On its part, Kathmandu has agreed to allow import of Indian
cars subject to self certification by Indian manufacturers and the
vehicles being Euro-1 compliant, he said.
</P>
<P>
In a separate report by the PTI, official sources were quoted
as saying that Koirala had canceled his proposed three-day visit
to Bangalore, a booming hi-tech city in south India, which was
scheduled to begin on Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
