<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top-seeded Agassi Ousted in Canadian TMS Tournament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Top-seeded Andre Agassi was ousted
Tuesday in the first round of the Tennis Masters Series (TMS)
tournament at York University in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
The three-time champion failed to advance to the quarter-finals
as he suffered in a 7-6 (7-4), 7-6 (7-6) loss to lightweight
Jerome Golmard of France.
</P>
<P>
It was the second time for the flamboyant American to suffer a
first round loss in 10 Canadian appearances since 1991.
</P>
<P>
The loss was his first against Golmard, who previously met
Agassi in the third-round Wimbledon in Rome last year and at the
Australian Open in 1995.
</P>
<P>
"Whether you won last year or last week, it doesn't matter.
What matters is today, and today he played better than I did,"
said Agassi, who won the Canadian tournament in 1992, 1994 and
1995.
</P>
<P>
This was Agassi's first tournament since Wimbledon on July 7,
when he lost to Patrick Rafter in five sets. Agassi suffered a
back injury in a minor car accident after Wimbledon and withdrew
from both the U.S. Davis Cup semifinal and last week's Mercedes-
Benz Cup.
</P>
<P>
It was also a hard day for Pete Sampras as well, as the No. 2
seed dropped the first set before rebounding for a 5-7, 6-2, 7-6 (
7-4) decision with qualifier Michael Llodra of France.
</P>
<P>
Sampras, recovering from a shin injury, admitted that "it was a
match where I didn't feel I was in control."
</P>
<P>
"It's not an easy match, first one out. It's a match where I'm
not going to get a lot of rhythm," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sampras will face Karim Alami of Morocco in second-round action
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The TMS tournament, formerly known as the Canadian Open, was
opened Monday night and continues until Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
