<HEADLINE> U.S. Names Men's Olympic Tennis Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Jeff Tarango, 31, was named
Tuesday to join Andre Agassi as the oldest member in the U.S. men'
s Olympic tennis squad.
</P>
<P>
Thus, the U.S. men's team will range from Agassi who owns the
career Grand Slam, to Tarango, better known for his tantrums than
for his play.
</P>
<P>
Also going to the Sydney Olympic Games are two veterans of
Michael Chang, who won his only Grand Slam title 11 years ago, and
Todd Martin, who has struggled since reaching the U.S. Open final
last year. Jared Palmer and Alex O'Brien will play for the doubles.
</P>
<P>
Missing are Pete Sampras, who won Wimbledon last month, and Jan-
Michael Gambill. Both declined to play, leaving a spot for the
81st-ranked Tarango, the team's oldest player. 
</P>
</TEXT>
