<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Serious Drought Hits Northeast China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Drought has affected more than
three quarters of summer crops in Northeast China's Liaoning
province as rain fall dropped to only half the average level since
May.
</P>
<P>
The most severe drought in the century has destroyed 80 percent
of crops in the western part of the province, where more than two
million people and 900,000 cattle are short of drinking water.
Villagers have to go several kilometers to fetch water.
</P>
<P>
More than 500 small and medium-sized reservoirs in the province
have dried up. Almost all rivers in western part of the province
have dried up.
</P>
<P>
Water shortages have spread from rural areas to the cities. The
largest reservoir in the province has only enough water to sustain
Shenyang, the capital, and Fushun city for three months.
</P>
<P>
Water supplies for agricultural production have suspended.
</P>
<P>
Chaoyang, Fuxin, Yingkou and other cities in the province have
already imposed water restrictions. Huludao city in the eastern
part of the province will have no drinking water by mid-August if
there is no rainfall.
</P>
<P>
The province has spent 300 million yuan to sink wells and
transport drinking water. The provincial government has recently
allocated 46 million yuan of emergency funds to relief farmers in
drought-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
Provincial officials said that the drought will greatly reduce
grain output this year and leave more than one million farmer
under on the brink of poverty.
</P>
<P>
They said that the province will face great difficulties in
keeping these farmers warm and fed in the coming winter.  
</P>
</TEXT>
