<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian, Iranian FMs Discuss Jerusalem Issue by Phone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The foreign ministers of Egypt and
Iran on Wednesday held talks by phone on Jerusalem, a holy city
whose fate proved to be the stumbling block in the latest
Palestinian-Israeli peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Amr Moussa of Egypt and Kamal Kharrazi of Iran discussed the
fate of Jerusalem, especially after the Palestinians and Israel
failed to reach a settlement at the Camp David summit held in the
United States, said a statement released by Iran's interest section
in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers examined possible steps their countries may
take towards helping resolve the dispute within the framework of
the Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC), the statement
added. It did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
Iran, who currently holds the OIC rotating presidency, is
reportedly to send envoys to Arab and Islamic countries in the
world in the coming days for talks on the fate of Jerusalem. Tehran
has opposed the Middle East peace process and called for armed
struggle to liberate the "Arab and Islamic lands" occupied by
Israel.
</P>
<P>
This was the second telephone conversation in as many days
between Moussa and Kharrazi to deal with Jerusalem issue in
particular, as the two countries were making efforts to improve
their severed relations.
</P>
<P>
Arab and Islamic countries support the Palestinian stand that
Israel should return Arab East Jerusalem it occupied in the 1967
Mideast War. The Palestinians want East Jerusalem as the capital of
their future independent state.
</P>
<P>
But Israel has insisted that Jerusalem is its "eternal and
indivisible" capital, a claim not recognized internationally.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
