<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bahamian-Flagged Ship Allowed to Cross Turkish Straits Conditionally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish Authorities has allowed
the Bahamian-flagged ship "Enterprise", which was not permitted to
pass through the Turkish Straits, to cross the straits
conditionally, the Anatolia News Agency reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The overlong ship, the flag of which is Bahamian not Romanian as
it was earlier stated, has been ordered to deposit one million U.S.
dollars as a safety guarantee and take necessary security measures
before crossing the narrow and traffic-busy straits.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish authorities said any ship whose length is more than
300 meters should get a report, which sets the conditions for a
safe passage, from either the Turkish Maritime Undersecretariat or
Istanbul Sea Traffic Control-Order Authority. "Enterprise" is 312
meters in overall length.
</P>
<P>
These conditions had been conveyed to the officials of the ship,
which was on its way from Australia to Constanta port of Romania,
transporting 192,554 tons of iron ore. But the officials on board
ignored the advice.
</P>
<P>
Turkish officials clarified that "Enterprise", which began to
anchor in the sea off the Dardanelles on July 16, should be
accompanied by five tugboats and one fire boat and guided by a
pilot captain.
</P>
<P>
If the ship fulfils the conditions as required, the traffic in
the Dardanelles and Bosphorus Straits will be closed in two ways
during its passage, they added.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is surrounded by the sea on three sides: the
Mediterranean in the south, the Aegean in the west and the Black
Sea in the north. The three seas are linked by the straits,
consisting from southwest to northeast, of the Dardanelles, the Sea
of Marmara and the Bosphorus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000802.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey, Iran Sign Natural Gas Protocol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Turkey signed here Wednesday a
protocol with Iran to buy natural gas from Iran, Turkey's Anatolia
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the protocol, Turkey will start purchasing 3
billion cubic metres of gas annually from Iran as of July 30, 2001
through a pipeline linking Iran's northwestern Tabriz with Ankara,
which is still under construction.
</P>
<P>
The protocol was finalized by Gokhan Yardim, director general of
Turkey's state-owned pipeline company BOTAS and Iranian Deputy Oil
Minister Mohammed Nejat who is on a two-day visit to Ankara
starting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is trying to overcome its energy shortage by importing
natural gas from Russia, Turkmenistan, Azerbaijan and Iran.
</P>
<P>
Under a 1996 agreement, Turkey pledged to buy natural gas from
Iran over 23 years.
</P>
<P>
Turkey had planned to complete its section of the pipeline by
January 1, 1999. But it failed to meet the deadline and has said
the pipeline will not be completed by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
With U.S. backing, Turkey is pursuing a multi-million-dollar
pipeline project to carry natural gas from Turkmenistan through the
Caspian Sea to Western markets via a conduit through Georgia and
Turkey. 
</P>
<P>
The United States, an arch rival of Iran, has voiced opposition
to the Turkish-Iranian deal on the grounds that it was a rival to
the trans-Caspian pipeline.
</P>
<P>
To appease Washington, Ankara has repeatedly said trans-Caspian
pipeline is a priority and even postponed the construction of the
Tabriz-Ankara pipeline.
</P>
<P>
But the trans-Caspian pipeline seems a long-term project whose
completion is nowhere in sight. Ever-growing energy demands
prompted Ankara to complete the project with Iran as well as
another one with Russia, which includes the construction of a new
gas pipeline beneath the Black Sea linking Russia and Turkey,
namely the Blue Stream.
</P>
<P>
The project, which started in February, was expected to deliver
365 billion cubic metres of gas from Russia to Turkey over 25 years
from 2001.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Turkey was rebuilding the Tarutina Compressor
station within its border with Ukraine to increase the capacity of
the current natural gas pipeline via Ukraine from Russia to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The pipeline carries 16 billion cubic meters of natural gas from
Russia to Turkey one year. With the operation of the compressor
station to be started in the fourth quarter of this year, the
capacity of the pipeline will increase by 3.8 billion cubic meters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
