<DOCNO> XIE20000802.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Funds Project to Repair East Timor's Water System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
said Wednesday that it has approved a project to repair East Timor
's badly-damaged water supply infrastructure and to re-establish
institutions and systems to operate the sector.
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued here, the ADB said the project will
be
financed by a 4.5-million-U.S. dollar grant from the Trust Fund
for East Timor and managed by ADB. The Fund has been established
with contributions from many donors.
</P>
<P>
The project will establish a water sector management and
investment program, including setting up a project management unit
under the United Nations Transitional Administration's Water and
Sanitation Authority, the ADB said.
</P>
<P>
East Timor's recent conflict saw the extensive destruction of
most infrastructure, including town and village water supply and
sanitation facilities. Houses were burned down and water
connections and meters were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
The total need for rehabilitating the sector is estimated at
almost 40 million dollars for the fiscal year 2001-2003, with
between 12 million dollars to 15 million dollars expected from the
Trust Fund, the Manila-based multilateral financial body said.
</P>
<P>
With current funds being allotted to various sectors, only 4.5
million dollars can be made available for the financial year 2000-
2001. As more funds become available, a follow-up project may be
developed, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
