<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dutch Glasshouse Growing Industry Expanding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The Dutch government said
Wednesday the glasshouse growing industry in the Netherlands is
still expanding.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 11,000 hectares of horticultural land is under glass,
which is 11 percent more than 10 years ago, the government said in
a press release.
</P>
<P>
The area under outdoor horticulture, on the other hand, is no
longer growing.
</P>
<P>
In the flower country, an area of 4,350 hectares is devoted to
growing vegetables under glass, while 63 percent of 6,000 hectares
of flower and potted plant growing under glass is used for cut
flowers, nearly half of which are roses and chrysanthemums.
</P>
<P>
The carnation is the only cut flower for which less area is
being used in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Currently, peppers have overtaken tomatoes as the biggest
vegetable product of the Dutch glasshouse growing industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
