<HEADLINE> Palestinians Call for Implementation of U.N. Resolutions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinians on Wednesday called
for full implementation of the United Nations Security Council
resolutions in a bid to end the half-century Arab-Israeli conflict.
</P>
<P>
The only way to peace in the Middle East is the "honest
implementation of the U.N. Security Council resolutions 242 and
338," Palestinian Ambassador to Egypt Zohdi al Qedra said after a
meeting between Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat in Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
Al Qedra criticized Israel for not honoring the resolutions of
international legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
The problem with the Israeli government is that it has always
evaded the responsibility to carry out the resolutions, which
demand that Israel withdraw from the Arab territories it occupied
in the 1967 Arab-Israeli war, he was quoted as saying by Egypt's
Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived in the Mediterranean port city earlier in the day
to brief Mubarak on his ongoing tour of Arab countries to rally
support for the Palestinian stands in peace talks with Israel. He
has visited Saudi Arabia, Yemen, Morocco, Tunisia, Algeria and
Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Following his tete-a-tete meeting with Mubarak, Arafat held a
90-minute session of talks with Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa at Borg el Arab airport, just outside Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the talks, Moussa reiterated Egypt's
support for a Palestinian state, which Arafat has said he may
declare on September 13, the deadline for Palestinian-Israeli final
status talks, even without a peace agreement with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Arafat left for Gaza after the talks without making statements.
He frequently visits Egypt to consult with Mubarak on the Mideast
peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
