<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Parliament Passes Early Election Bill in Preliminary Vote 1st lead-writethru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 2 (Xinhua) -- In the preliminary reading,
Israel's Knesset, or Parliament, Wednesday morning passed a bill
calling for dissolving the Knesset and holding a new election ,
dealing another blow to Prime Minister Ehud Barak and his peace
efforts.
</P>
<P>
A total of 61 Knesset members voted for the bill, submitted by
the major opposition Likud legislators Silvan Shalom and Limor
Livnat, while 51 voted against it and six legislators abstained,
Israeli television reported.
</P>
<P>
Although three more readings are required for the bill to go
into effect, the parliamentary vote again showed that Barak's
political strength is further shrinking after the botched Camp
David summit talks with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and U.S.
President Bill Clinton last month.
</P>
<P>
Shortly before the vote, Foreign Minister David Levy announced
his resignation from the cabinet due to Barak's "too much
concessions" at the Camp David peace talks, which aimed to reach an
Israeli-Palestinian agreement but failed to deliver the good
finally.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Barak's presidential candidate Shimon Peres also
suffered a humiliating defeat by Moshe Katsav, the Likud's underdog
candidate, in the Knesset's presidential secret ballot.
</P>
<P>
Barak's government narrowly survived an opposition-sponsored no-
confidence bill Monday night.
</P>
<P>
The early-election bill had been expected to be passed in
Wednesday's preliminary reading, as Barak's government now only
holds 40 seats in the 120-member Knesset after the withdrawal of
Levy and his two-seat Geshar party from the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Ahead of the Camp David summit, 26 MKs from three right-wing
parties in Barak's ruling coalition, Shas, Yisrael Ba'aliya and
National Religious Party, already withdrew their support for Barak
because of his readiness to go to Camp David for the talks.
</P>
<P>
The government defeated an identical early-election motion in
the first reading in June, and at that time, it was said that the
oppositions will not be able to re-submit such a bill in another
six months.
</P>
<P>
However, considering the massive resignation from the government
and the controversial Camp David talks, Knesset Speaker Avraham
Burg last month agreed to the opposition's demand to resurrect the
bill.
</P>
<P>
To Barak's relief, the Knesset will begin its summer recess
after Wednesday's session and will not reconvene until October 30.
So now the prime minister has three most-needed months to form a
new and more solid coalition or to prepare for new elections.
</P>
<P>
Likud's Shalom, one of the early-election bill's sponsors, has
pledged that he will ask the Knesset to hold special sessions
during the recess to prepare for the early-election bill's further
readings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
