<HEADLINE> Sudan Hails IMF Decision to Resume its Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The Sudanese government has
hailed the decision by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) to
restore the country's membership in the organization as a big step
that will promote the government's efforts to normalize its ties
with world financing institutions and to attract more foreign
investments.
</P>
<P>
The El-Alwan newspaper Wednesday quoted Foreign Minister Mustafa
Othman Ismail as saying that the resumption of Sudan's IMF
membership reflects the government's seriousness in implementing
its economic policies.
</P>
<P>
The executive authority of the IMF decided Tuesday at a meeting
held in Washington to lift the temporary ban imposed on Sudan which
deprived it of the voting rights and other advantages.
</P>
<P>
The IMF has said the decision was made in appreciation of the
economic progress achieved by the North African country since 1997,
as well as the country's efforts to resume the repayment of some of
its debts to the IMF.
</P>
<P>
In August 9, 1993, the IMF decided to impose a temporary ban on
granting loans to Sudan after it failed to repay about 1.48 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Former Finance Minister Abdel-Rahim Hamdi said the IMF decision
helps to reschedule Sudan's commercial and banking debts as well as
the IMF debts, which amount to billions of dollars. Besides, Sudan
will be able to join the debt exemption projects decided by the
donors countries.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the most concrete result of the decision is that it
has sent a signal to investors and international financing
institutions that Sudan is not economically isolated any more.
</P>
</TEXT>
