<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Ruling, Opposition Parties Gear Up for Battle Over New Draft Constitution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government of
ruling People's Alliance (PA) and opposition parties have geared
up for a major battle over the new draft constitution which is
expected to be presented to the parliament on Thursday, party
officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
General Secretary of the Sinhala Urumaya (heritage) and former
parliamentarian Tilak Karunaratne said that several moves are
being made behind the scenes to prevent the government from trying
to get a required two-thirds majority vote in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, "I cannot disclose some of our planned
actions for tomorrow."
</P>
<P>
Petitions have been filed in Sri Lanka's Supreme Court by the
Sinhala Urumaya, the main opposition United National Party (UNP),
Buddhist monks and the Center for Policy Alternatives to prevent
the government from presenting the new draft constitution to the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The government of President Chandrika Kumaratunga on Monday
approved the draft constitution during a special cabinet meeting
and decided to present the draft to the parliament on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The government on Tuesday submitted the draft to the Supreme
Court for advice on the process of adoption. The court said
Wednesday that they will convey their decision to President
Kumaratunga and Parliamentary Speaker K.B. Ratnayake on Thursday
on the proposed new draft constitution.
</P>
<P>
The General Secretary of the PA, D.M. Jayaratne said the draft
would be presented on Thursday at a special parliamentary sitting
and taken up for debate on August 8 (next Tuesday).
</P>
<P>
Jayaratne said most minority Tamil parties had pledged support
to pass the draft constitution while the UNP said they were
awaiting a copy of the draft to determine their own stand on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
The parliament, which is situated at Kotte in eastern suburban
Colombo, is expected to be tense on Thursday as the Buddhist monks
and the left-wing People's Liberation Front have threatened to
protest in front of the parliament, party officials said.
</P>
<P>
There has been a wide spate of protests against the government'
s new draft constitution which is widely believed to grant greater
autonomy to minority Tamils in the north and east where Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) rebels have been waging a bloody war
against government troops since 1983.
</P>
<P>
The draft constitution aims to end the long-running civil war
by devolving more powers to regional councils and partly meeting
LTTE demand for an independent state called Eelam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
