<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government on
Wednesday accused Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) rebels
of conscripting child soldiers as young as seven years old to
fight for the long-running separatist war.
</P>
<P>
A 14-year-old Tamil girl named Indira was forcibly taken away
by a LTTE cadre known as Tanam Akka to a rebel camp in 1993 when
she was only seven years old and was studying in Grade 2 at
Padathurapalli in Mankulam area in northern Sri Lanka, said a
statement issued by the government's Special Media Information
Center.
</P>
<P>
It said the girl had been trained to handle T56 rifle and hand
grenades. She was also given the cadre number Ena 2173 by the LTTE
rebels who have been fighting for a separate homeland called Eelam
in Sri Lanka's north and east since 1983.
</P>
<P>
The girl surrendered to government troops last month at
Nagarkovil in the northern Jaffna peninsula, the scene of weeks of
fierce fighting during April and May between government troops and
LTTE rebels who want to retake their former stronghold of Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
Indira was quoted as saying that most of the 15 women LTTE
rebels in her group had been around her age and died during
fighting with government troops. 
</P>
