<HEADLINE> Strike Called in Nepal to Protest Against Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 2 (Xinhua) -- A general strike is observed
Wednesday in Kathmandu and two adjoining cities by an opposition
party to protest against a controversial citizenship bill.
</P>
<P>
Shops, schools, factories and some offices are closed while
traffic in the valley are suspended, with almost all vehicles off
the road, during the one-day strike called by the Communist Party
of Nepal-Marxist and Leninist (CPN-ML).
</P>
<P>
The few vehicles that dared to appear on roads were stoned by
the supporters of the strike, but no one was injured.
</P>
<P>
CPN-ML has denounced the recent government act of pushing
through a controversial citizenship bill because it will entitle
large numbers of Indians Nepalese citizenship and at the same time
opens the floodgates to influx of Indians through the 1700km-long
open border between Nepal and India.
</P>
<P>
The strike is also aimed at urging the government to take tough
measures against a 13.6 km-long barrage built by India recently
along Nepal-India border that was reported to have flooded some
Nepali villages in the border area.
</P>
<P>
More than 500 people become homeless due to the flood while
more villages and land will be affected during the monsoon season
from mid-June to September every year. 
</P>
