<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Technique to Treat Tooth Decay Shown in Brussels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Dentists attending an
international conference here have learned a new technique to
repair damaged or decayed teeth which incorporates the use of
lasers, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Belgian dental experts said the new laser technique will soon
be used to remove tooth decay. Dentists were told they would not
have to anesthetize the area surrounding the damaged teeth as
often as they do now.
</P>
<P>
The laser therapy for teeth is virtually painless unless the
cavity is near the nerve, in which case it will still be necessary
to numb the gums.
</P>
<P>
The laser technique can also work preventively, according to
the experts. Tests have also shown that the parts of a tooth that
have been treated by laser are more resistant to decay.
</P>
<P>
Of the 8,000 dentists in Belgium, about 200 already use the
laser technique. However, this kind of dental treatment is very
expensive. Experts expect that further development of the
technique will lower costs.
</P>
<P>
Experts believe that use of the painless laser technique for
treatment will be widespread throughout the world within 10 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
