<HEADLINE> Standard Chartered Hong Kong Posts Record Trading Profit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Standard Chartered Hong Kong,
one of the leading banks of Hong Kong, reported Wednesday that its
trading profits grew by 95 percent in the first half of the year
to a record 1.98 billion HK dollars (254 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The total deposits grew by 11.2 percent while total loan
increased by 4.8 percent. It recorded a 2.9 percent of net
interest margin. The charge for debts plunged from 1.36 billion HK
dollars (174 million U.S. dollars) to 400 million HK dollars (51.3
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Commenting on these results, Mervyn Davies, executive director
of the Standard Chartered Group, said "this has been the most
profitable six months in our long history in Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
"Despite tough market competition, we have grown our overall
mortgage portfolio. We have also continued to rapidly grow our
business in key products like credit cards, custody and cash
management," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to report from London, the British bank Standard
Chartered, which operates mainly in Asia, increased pre-tax
profits by 31 percent to 356 million pounds (537 million U.S.
dollars) in the first half of the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
