<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Gives UNIFIL Green Light to Extend Deployment in South </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese President Emile Lahoud and
Prime Minister Salim Hoss have decided to give the United Nations
Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL) green light to deploy throughout
south Lebanon along the border with Israel, An Nahar newspaper
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
UNIFIL command and the Lebanese army command will discuss the
timing of the extended deployment on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan's lieutenant for peacekeeping
operations Bernard Millet flew in Tuesday night to oversee the last
stage of the UNIFIL deployment.
</P>
<P>
Millet is scheduled to meet with Hoss Wednesday before heading
to Naqoura, the UNIFIL headquarters, which is about 100 kilometers
south of Beirut. He is due to discuss with the UNIFIL command on
the time frame for the extended deployment operation, after which
he will go to Israel on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
UNIFIL troops have already fanned out in six locations of the
liberated zone and have yet to roll into 13 other locations to firm
up their control along the Lebanese side of the Blue Line, which
was drawn by the United Nations to verify Israel's withdrawal from
south Lebanon on May 24.
</P>
<P>
The An Nahar newspaper noted that the Yaroun verification was
made possible after UNIFIL's Ukrainian sappers Tuesday night
finished dismantling a total of 101 anti-personnel mines and 11
anti-tank mines left behind by Israeli troops after the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Michael Murr told reporters on Tuesday that a
task force of 500 Lebanese army troops and 500 policemen was
standing by to be deployed in the liberated zone 48 hours after
UNIFIL extends its own deployment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
