<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli FM Resigns From Barak's Government 2nd lead-writethru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister David
Levy resigned on Wednesday from the government led by Prime
Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
In an announcement at his office inside the Knesset
(parliament), Levy said he has submitted his resignation letter to
Barak Wednesday morning, in which he detailed his reasons for
resignation.
</P>
<P>
"I can not accept Prime Minister Barak's peace policies
concerning the negotiations with the Palestinians, because Barak
had made too many concessions to the Palestinians at the Camp David
summit, particularly on the Jerusalem issue," Levy said.
</P>
<P>
"Under such circumstances, it is impossible for me to continue
to be the foreign minister in the government," he added.
</P>
<P>
Under certain government regulations, Levy's resignation will
come into effect within 48 hours after submitting the letter of
resignation.
</P>
<P>
Barak told reporters at the Knesset that he respected Levy's
decision to resign from the government.
</P>
<P>
"I respected Foreign Minister Levy's decision, but his
resignation will not affect my efforts to continue the peace
process with the Palestinians and I will continue to try to reach a
peace agreement with the Palestinians," Barak added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said, he will continue to exert his efforts in the
coming days to put together a new coalition government.
</P>
<P>
Levy's Gesher (Bridge) party formed the political alliance of
One Israel with Barak's Labor party during the May 1999 general
elections. His party has two seats in the 120-member Knesset on the
slot of One Israel Knesset list.
</P>
<P>
Levy's resignation not only reduced the number of cabinet
ministers to 12 from 23, but also further put Barak's crippling
coalition into the absolute minority in the Knesset.
</P>
<P>
Barak asked Levy on Tuesday to delay his resignation by a week.
But Levy replied that if by Wednesday morning the prime minister
does not make serious efforts to form a national unity government,
he will submit his resignation and vote for the bills to dissolve
the Knesset which comes up for preliminary reading Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Levy was at odds with Barak since May, when Barak ordered Public
Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami, instead of the foreign minister,
to conduct secret peace talks with Palestinian Legislative Council
Speaker Ahmed Qurei.
</P>
<P>
Levy also refused to attend the Camp David summit with Barak,
citing the Palestinian side was not ready to make concessions on
all key issues in the final-status talks and the timing was not
ripe for the summit.
</P>
<P>
Levy's resignation will cause more political hardship for Barak,
who is in fact facing a political mess at home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
