<DOCNO> XIE20000802.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Assembly Agrees not to Stage Special Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- All factions of the Indonesia's
People's Consultative Assembly (MPR), the country's highest law-
making body, agreed here Wednesday not to turn the next annual
session of the assembly into a special session.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to stick to its regular session agenda under
which incumbent President Abdurrahman Wahid will not deliver an
accountability speech for his nine months in office.
</P>
<P>
This means that Wahid may only face questions and critical
evaluations from the members of the assembly but not to face an
impeachment against him.
</P>
<P>
At a plenary session of the Assembly's Working Committee
presided over by Speaker of the Assembly Amien Rais, Posdam
Hutasoit, chairman of the Special Ad Hoc Committee in charge of
the forthcoming session agenda, said that the committee has
arranged a schedule and expected to be endorsed by the first
plenary session on August 7.
</P>
<P>
"The president will only deliver a progress report speech, not
an accountability speech," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hutasoit's statement has "calmed down" certain parties in the
country who have been worry over possible moves from the president
's political opponents to use the annual session to impeach Wahid.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the country's five most influential leaders have
also agreed to consider the next annual session of the Assembly as
an ordinary session during which incumbent Wahid will not face an
impeachment. The leaders who attended the meeting in Yogyakarta
are President Abdurrahman Wahid, Speaker of the Assembly Amien
Rais, Vice President Megawati Soekarnoputeri, Speaker of the
Parliament Akbar Tandjung and Governor of Yogyakarta Province
Sultan Hamengkubuwono X.
</P>
<P>
The assembly is due to hold its annual session on August 7-18.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
