<HEADLINE> Indonesian Gov't Tightens Security for Foreign Embassies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Following a deadly bomb blast
occurred at the Philippine Embassy to Indonesia on Tuesday, the
Indonesian authorities has issued an order to tighten security for
foreign embassies in the capital city.
</P>
<P>
Antara news agency quoted Chief of the National Police (Polri)
Gen.Roesdihardjo and Commander of the Indonesian Military (TNI)
Adm.Widodo as saying here Wednesday that security will also be
tightened around the offices of foreign companies in the capital.
</P>
<P>
Roesdihardo said that he has instructed Chief Inspector of the
Jakarta Police Gen. Nurfaizi to check foreigners in Jakarta,
particularly those coming from the Philippines, adding that the
bomb blast incident might have been organized by Filipinos as well
as Indonesians.
</P>
<P>
"I have instructed the chief inspector of the Jakarta police to
check all guests from our neighbors in the north (the Philippines)
staying in all hotels here," he said.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday noon, a powerful bomb exploded in front of the
Philippine Embassy building in Central Jakarta, killing two people
and injuring at least 23 others including Philippine Ambassador
Leonides T Caday.
</P>
<P>
The bomb, the second explosion in the capital for less than one
month, damaged a wall of the residence of the Philippine
Ambassador and the fence of the Bulgarian Embassy. The explosion,
which left a huge orifice near by the Philippine Embassy and also
was felt up to 500 meters from the location and formed a huge
black mushroom-shaped smoke, was believed to be TNT (trinitroluene)
bomb, a kind of a powerful bomb.
</P>
<P>
President Abdurrahman Wahid and Foreign Minister Alwi Shihab
said that the Philippine Muslim separatist could have been behind
the incident. While various sides have voiced suspicions that the
bombing was work of the Muslim separatist group in the southern
Philippine of the MILF (Moro Islamic Liberation Front) or
Indonesians who are trying to discredit the government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Speaker of the People's Consultative Assembly Amien
Rais suggested that the culprits of Tuesday's bomb blast might
involve people who were in Jakarta. "It would be too much to
accuse foreign parties. I think the perpetrators came from around
here," he was quoted by Antara as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
