<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ILO Facilitates Publicity Against Child Labor in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 2 (Xinhua) -- International Labor
Organization (ILO has signed an agreement with Nepal's Medialine
to facilitate the publicity against child labor in Nepal, ILO said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement signed here Tuesday is aimed at mobilizing media
and their organizations to speak for immediate abolition of the
worst forms of child labor in Nepal, a press release by ILO said.
</P>
<P>
It is also intended to achieve an increased awareness and
understanding among both government and the public on their roles
in combating child labors, the release said.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Medialine is to produce video films on
child workers, tele-serials on the plights of the working children
and street dramas in local dialects against the practice of
employing children.
</P>
<P>
"These are some of the activities that aim at creating a
critical mass that will spontaneously advocate against child labor,
" said the release.
</P>
<P>
Medialine, a private media company in Nepal, will also develop
codes of conduct for Nepalese journalists for reporting on child
labor issues in collaboration with media organizations, civil
society and journalists associations, according to the release.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that of the 10 million Nepalese children under
14 years old, there are at least 2.5 million child laborers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
