<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Darkest Day of Kashmir  By Zhou Xiaozheng </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 2 (Xinhua) -- For many years to come, August
1 might be remembered as the darkest day of Kashmir: within less
than 24 hours, nearly 90 people, most of them innocent civilians,
fell at the gunpoint of ruthless militants across the region.
</P>
<P>
The Kashmir valley is in no case unfamiliar with mass bloodshed,
not after it has triggered two wars between India and Pakistan and
has witnessed thousands of deaths in the past decade of militancy
and border skirmishes. However, it is still extremely rare for
this land to see so much innocent blood being shed overnight.
</P>
<P>
Newsmen in the Indian capital were kept busy all Wednesday
morning updating their stories with latest casualty reports from
Kashmir. While the morning newspapers put the death toll at a mere
23 to 27, the latest figure released by the quasi-official Press
Trust of India (PTI) in the afternoon sharply raised the number of
victims to 88.
</P>
<P>
Even Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee failed to catch up
with the rocketing death toll. While briefing the Lok Sabha, or
the lower house of the Indian parliament this morning, he said
there had been 60 victims of militant attacks in Kashmir since
Tuesday, though conceding that the figure was only "tentative".
</P>
<P>
According to media reports seen here, the first of a series of
bloody attacks, or, to be more exactly, massacres, occurred at
around 6 p.m. Tuesday at Pahalgam town in west Kashmir. A group of
militants broke into a pilgrim camp in the suburbs of Pahalgam and
fired indiscriminately at the crowd, who were cooking their
dinners.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-two people, including 21 pilgrims heading for north
India's holy Amarnath Cave and local shopkeepers and porters, were
killed and dozens of others injured. This has been the heaviest
civilian casualty in one single militant attack since March 20
this year, when 35 Sikh residents were massacred in south Kashmir
amid U.S. President Bill Clinton's visit to India.
</P>
<P>
Just four hours later, another group of heavily-armed militants
descended on a brick kiln at Mir Bazar in west Kashmir's Anantnag
district. They brought 18 male laborers out of their residences
and shot them in the face of their wives and children.
</P>
<P>
The militants' killing spree continued throughout the night. In
the wee hours of Wednesday, they entered the house of a
surrendered former militant and killed all seven members of the
family in the frontier district of Kupwara in north Kashmir; they
also gunned down 11 Hindus in a remote village in Doda district in
southwest Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the aforementioned incidents, the militants had
attacked at least three other places late Tuesday night and early
Wednesday morning, media reports said.
</P>
<P>
A mixed feeling of shock, sorrow and fury gripped the Indian
capital as the news of the massacres reached here. Indian
President K R Narayanan, Vice President Krishan Kant, Prime
Minister Vajpayee and Home Affairs Minister L.K. Advani all
condemned the killings, calling them "heinous acts" representing "
the height of barbarism and inhumanity".
</P>
<P>
The news also caused uproar in the Indian parliament, which is
in its monsoon session here, as the legislators stopped normal
discussions and examination of bills and demanded the government
to explain on the Kashmir situation. The Lok Sabha had to be
adjourned for two hours.
</P>
<P>
Both Vajpayee and Advani, as well as local officials in Kashmir,
believed that Tuesday's massacres were conducted by militants who
wanted to sabotage the central government's recent peace
initiative in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, Hizbul Mujahideen, a major militant outfit in
Kashmir, announced a unilateral ceasefire, to which the Indian
government responded on Sunday with cessation of all military
operations against the outfit and an offer for peace talks with it.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday afternoon, Hizbul Mujahideen took a positive step
further by naming its negotiator, and at the same time called for
a complete ceasefire between all militant groups in Kashmir and
the Indian government. Many believe this has cast the first light
of hope on a possible end to the decade-long militancy and
violence in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
However, there were obviously quite a few other militant
outfits who didn't want to see peace in Kashmir at all. Following
the Hizbul Mujahideen announcement, the region just enjoyed one
day of relative peace and tranquillity, with only one minor
incident of violence reported. Starting on Monday, militancy-
related violence has drastically stepped up across the region.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, an army transit camp in north Kashmir was attacked
by militants with rockets and grenades, with six army personnel
killed and seven others injured. Then on Tuesday evening, as if to
slam the door at Hizbul Mujahideen's ceasefire call, the large-
scale killing of civilians.
</P>
<P>
"It seems that some of the militants are frightened of the
prospects of peace and chose these innocent pilgrims as soft
targets," Advani said after learning the first massacre in
Pahalgam.
</P>
<P>
In his address to the parliament, Vajpayee also virtually
accused Pakistan of being behind the killings in Kashmir, claiming
that the killings were the handiwork of elements "operating at the
behest of Pakistan or getting directions from it".
</P>
<P>
However, the Indian side didn't seem to be able to submit any
hard evidence on any Pakistani involvement in the killings. There
was even no militant outfit to claim responsibility for them.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some diplomatic analysts here asked if it was wise
and practical for the Indian government to pursue peace in Kashmir
without taking Pakistan into account, especially as New Delhi had
always accused Islamabad of backing and directing militants in the
region.
</P>
<P>
To the great relief of most Kashmir people longing for a
peaceful and calm life, the Indian government promised on
Wednesday it would continue with its current efforts to restore
peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
"It (the killing) is a desperate act and it only proves that
the government is proceeding on the right track," said Advani, who
is seeing to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Nothing would deflect India from pursuing the path of peace in
Kashmir, Vajpayee told the legislators, adding: "We will overcome
all these difficulties."
</P>
<P>
But for the families and relatives of those massacre victims,
they might just hope their kinsfolk's blood was not shed in vain
and the dark night of August 1 was just one of those darkest hours
before a bright dawn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
