<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIVB Nets Television Rights Bonanza </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEVILLE, Spain, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The International
Volleyball Federation (FIVB) on Tuesday signed 150 million United
States dollars as television rights for its worldwide competitions.
</P>
<P>
The deal, signed with five television networks from Japan, the
United States and Brazil, is part of a 400-million-dollar package
for the next decade for the development of the sport.
</P>
<P>
"With the new TV agreements, the television rights allow the
FIVB to secure revenues of more than 400 million U.S. dollars for
the next 10 years," said Ruben Acosta, president of the 218-member
federation, the largest of any single sport in the world.
</P>
<P>
Kiribati, an island state in the Pacific, became the 218th
member of the FIVB on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The television networks that signed with the FIVB were NTV, TBS
and Fuji Television from Japan, TV Globo of Brazil and ESPN
International from the United States.
</P>
<P>
More revenues meant more prize money for the volleyballers
around the world. The FIVB, the governing body of the world's
volleyball sport, said on Tuesday that prize money for next year's
World League will increase by 50 percent to reach 15 million
dollars while the beach volleyball world tour will also increase
its purse to 5 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
With their deals with the FIVB, NTV has acquired the world
television rights for the 2001 and 2005 men's and women's grand
champions cup in Japan; TBS has acquired territorial rights for
the 2002 and 2006 men's and women's world championships; Fuji
Television has acquired territorial rights for the 2003, 2007 and
2011 men's and women's world cup in Japan.
</P>
<P>
TV Globo has acquired territorial broadcasting rights for the
2003 world cups, world league, beach volleyball world tour between
2001 and 2005 plus the beach volleyball world championship in 2003
and grand prix between 2000 and 2005.
</P>
<P>
ESPN International has acquired with its deal worldwide
broadcasting rights, excluding Japan, for the 2002, 2006 and 2010
world men's championships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
