<HEADLINE> FIVB Chief Welcome to Be IOC Member: Samaranch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEVILLE, Spain, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The chief of the world
sport of volleyball got on Tuesday a nice surprise that he will be
welcome to be a member of the International Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
The news was broken out by the IOC President Juan Antonio
Samaranch himself who attended the opening session of the 27th
International Volleyball Federation (FIVB) congress.
</P>
<P>
"Last week the IOC Executive Board decided to propose some new
candidates for IOC membership from among presidents of the
international federations and the national Olympic committees,"
said Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
"The president of the FIVB was among them and we are ready to
welcome your president as an IOC member," the IOC chief told the
FIVB congress.
</P>
<P>
Samaranch said that his institution would also like to increase
the number of seats in its executive board but he would rather
respect the autonomy of the FIVB.
</P>
<P>
The IOC chief told the world volleyball congress that changes
are needed to make sports more fantastic. He said that he
approved the recent changes regarding the rally point system, the
introduction of the libero, colored balls, the net fault and rules
on the player uniforms.
</P>
<P>
"If the international federations don't change their rules for
television, their sports will be in trouble," said Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
The FIVB has just signed a television rights deal with five
networks from Japan, the United States and Brazil, worth 150
million U.S. dollars in total. The deal was part of the FIVB's
400-million-dollar package for the next decade of development.
</P>
<P>
Ruben Acosta, president of the International Volleyball
Federation, said after the opening session of the congress that he
would rather see no more changes for the next four years to
maintain the stability of the sport.
</P>
<P>
He said that he agreed with Samaranch on his point that changes
are inevitable for the development of sports. "But they should
not happen often and in difficult situations," said the FIVB chief.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
