<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Opposition Rejects Taliban's "Hollow" Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's opposition
alliance Wednesday rejected an offer of amnesty from the supreme
leader of the ruling Taliban militia, saying his words were hollow
and their fight would go on.
</P>
<P>
Opposition spokesman Mohammad Habeel said Taliban chief Mulla
Mohammad Omar's call on the opposition forces to surrender was "
just hollow words and a waste of time to hear."
</P>
<P>
"This is not something new. Our people have fought a jehad (
holy war) against the Russians," he said, quoted by reports
reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Omar Tuesday offered amnesty to his opponents and guaranteed
the safety of those who joined his regime, the Islamic Emirate of
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
"The Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan will protect life and
property of all those who join the government," Omar said in a
statement from his headquarters in southern Afghan city of
Kandahar.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban now control about 90 percent of the country, except
small pockets in rugged northeastern areas controlled by former
Defense Minister Ahmed Shah Masood.
</P>
<P>
Omar's call to surrender follows Taliban advances in
northeastern Baghlan and Takhar provinces last week, where the
militia captured two opposition-held towns slashing Masood's
supply lines from Tajikistan to key positions near Kabul 
</P>
</TEXT>
