<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Capital Outflow Accelerated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's capital outflow during
the first five months this year has been accelerated, which
amounted 7 billion U.S. dollars, compared with a total 8 billion
dollars for the whole of 1999, according to an official report
issued here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report, released by the Bank of Thailand (BOT), said that
the capital outflow is likely to persist as the private sector and
public agencies will have to continue accelerating their debt
repayments of foreign loans.
</P>
<P>
Foreign capital flight from the Stock Exchange of Thailand is
also another factor aggravating the situation as foreign investors
have continued to sell stocks for some time, it said.
</P>
<P>
"The net outflow of funds is largely due to the debt repayments
of foreign loans. In a situation where local interest rates are
less than those in foreign markets, local funds inevitably lose
when mobilized," a local analyst noted.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the outflow, he believed that the country would
continue to witness the trend for some time. This is due
especially to the U.S. Central Bank's increasing of its interest
rates to tame its economy, which would result in a widening
interest gap between local and overseas markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000802.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Tops Car Sales in ASEAN for First Six Months 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia recorded the
highest new motor vehicle sales in ASEAN for the first six months
of this year amid improvement in the region's economies, newly-
elected ASEAN Automotive Federation (AAF) President Aishah Ahmad
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In releasing the latest sales figures at a press conference in
Petaling Jaya near here, Aishah, who is also the Malaysia
Automotive Association president, said Malaysia remained at the
top with 163,721 units followed by Indonesia with 126,944 units
and Thailand at 122,933 units.
</P>
<P>
She said Malaysia was projected to continue to top the list for
the whole of this year with sales of 350,000 units, reflecting a
21.3 percent increase from last year, she said, adding this will
be followed by Thailand at 280,000 units or 28.2 percent more from
last year and Indonesia at 240,000 units or 155.7 percent increase
from last year.
</P>
<P>
She attributed Malaysia's excellent performance to the fact
that it was the first country in the region to recover from the
economic crisis and the increased consumer confidence was
supported by the country's political stability.
</P>
<P>
The AAF comprises eight out of 10 ASEAN countries namely Brunei,
Indonesia Laos, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and
Vietnam. The other two ASEAN members are Cambodia and Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
According to the AAF president, total sales of new motor
vehicles sales for the whole region in the first half of 2000
stood at 498,086 units, just 32.8 percent less than the whole of
last year.
</P>
<P>
"As the region's economies continue to record strong growth
this year, confidence is now building up among the people and they
are buying more cars," she said.
</P>
<P>
Due to the encouraging picture in the first half of this year,
she said total sales of new motor vehicles for the whole of 2000
in this region would reach the projected 1,059,913 units.
</P>
<P>
"The figure continues to support the global belief that the
ASEAN region is still a very important market with great growth
potential," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000802.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Launches Plan to Ensure Health Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Uganda has drawn up a five-year
Health Sector Strategic Plan to ensure a core package of health
care services for all Ugandans, according to a press release
available on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The principal aims of the plan are to improve access of the
population to the Uganda National Minimum Health Care Package (
UNMHCP), improve the quality of delivery of the package and reduce
inequalities in accessing health services," said the release
issued by F. G. Omaswa, director general of Uganda Health Services.
</P>
<P>
Particular attention will be paid to training, recruitment and
motivation of qualified staff, the release said, noting that
rehabilitation and improvement of the performance of existing
facilities will be stressed.
</P>
<P>
The release said that communities will be mobilized to
participate in the management and monitoring of health services.
</P>
<P>
Better health is an essential contribution to poverty
eradication, the release quoted Minister of Health Crispus Kiyonga
as saying. "Ill health is expensive and people who are sick can
not produce wealth," said Kiyonga.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that the economic loss from malaria alone ranged
between 1 to 3 percent of the annual Gross Domestic Product. "This
loss translates into millions of dollars annually," said the
minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000802.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 13 on Trial in Switzerland for Financial Cheating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Twelve Swiss and one Italian went
on trial Wednesday for their role in the European Kings Club "
pyramid" scheme which collapsed five years ago, Swiss Radio
International reported.
</P>
<P>
The 13 men were accused of defrauding 94,000 investors in
Switzerland, Germany and Austria of 360 million U.S. dollars, with
some facing additional charges of violating Swiss banking law and
membership of a criminal organization, court official Peter Alex
Mueller was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors said the 13 were low-ranking figures in the
scheme's Berne branch, and that they had helped to con more than 1,
500 investors out of 17.5 million Swiss francs (about 11 million U.
S. dollars) in the Swiss capital. Their bosses were jailed for
fraud in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Swiss investigators, who have led inquiries into the scheme in
12 cantons, believe that as many as 30,000 people in Switzerland
have been defrauded of between 200-300 million francs (about 125.7-
188.6 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Kings Club was founded in Germany in 1991 and set out to
exploit fears about giving up the Deutsche Mark for the euro, by
offering staggering annual returns of up to 72 percent. As more
investors were drawn by the high rates of interest, the scheme
snowballed, spreading to Switzerland a year later.
</P>
<P>
Kings Club representatives sold investment certificates for 1,
400 francs (about 880 dollars) with the promise they would be
worth 2,400 francs (about 1508.6 dollars) within a year. But
investors were only granted the privilege to "join the club" on
condition they signed up 15 new members within a month.
</P>
<P>
Pyramid schemes rely on existing investors to recruit new
members to finance high yields with their initial outlay. The
Kings Club collapsed in late 1995, when it failed to find enough
new recruits to finance the returns of those higher up the pyramid.
</P>
<P>
Berne's Economic Criminal Court will try the 13 defendants in
two stages. The Italian and six Swiss appeared in court on
Wednesday with the verdict expected on August 15. The others will
go on trial a week later and the verdict is scheduled for August
29. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
