<HEADLINE> Israeli FM Resigns From Barak's Government 1st lead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister David
Levy resigned from Prime Minister Ehud Barak's coalition government
here on Wednesday due to his disagreement to Barak's concessions to
the Palestinians over the Jerusalem issue.
</P>
<P>
In an announcement at his office inside the Knesset
(parliament), Levy said he has submitted his resignation letter to
Barak Wednesday morning, in which he detailed his reasons for
resignation.
</P>
<P>
"I can not accept Prime Minister (Ehud) Barak's peace policies
concerning the negotiations with the Palestinians, because Barak
had made too much concessions to the Palestinians at the Camp David
summit, particularly on the Jerusalem issue," Levy said.
</P>
<P>
"Under such circumstances, it is impossible for me to continue
to be the foreign minister in the government," Levy added.
</P>
<P>
Levy's resignation has been viewed as a new blow to Barak's
crippled government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
