<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Ends Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 2 (Xinhua) - The Australian sharemarket ended
stronger Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The S&AMP;P/ASX 200 closed 16.3 points higher at 3270.3. The all
ordinaries index closed 14.5 points higher at 3232.3.
</P>
<P>
Overall, 594.46 million shares were traded for a value of 1.52
billion Australian dollars (886.16 million U.S. dollars). There
were 565 rising stocks, 831 falling stocks and 519 unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The Reserve Bank of Australia today lifted the cash rate to 6.
25 percent from 6.0 percent. it was the fifth increase in the cash
rate since November 1999. A rate rise normally crimps demand for
stocks as companies' borrowing costs rise, which in turn could
dent profit growth. However The Australian sharemarket shrugged
off it and investors took the opportunity to buy stocks hit by
recent falls.
</P>
<P>
NAB jumped 40 Australian cents to 25.15 Australian dollars and
most other banks also rose. Westpac gained 10 cents to 12.25
Australian dollars, Commonwealth rose two cents to 27.82
Australian dollars while ANZ shed 10.7 cents to 12.723 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
News Corp rose 42.7 cents to 21.317 Australian dollars while
its preferred stock added 18.6 to 18.436 Australian dollars. Seven
jumped 25 cents to 7.70 Australian dollars, while PBL fell three
cents to 13.12 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Within the resources sector, BHP fell two cents to 18.10
Australian dollars, Rio Tinto rose 14.4 cents to 25.80 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Among the telcos, Telstra slipped two cents to 7.11 Australian
dollars, and C&AMP;W Optus added nine cents to 5.09 Australian dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
