<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cancer Hero Armstrong Leads U.S. Olympic Cycling Squad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Lance Armstrong, a cancer hero
who won two consecutive Tour de France in the past two years, will
lead a five-member U.S. men's road racing squad for the Syndey
Olympic Games, said the U.S. Cycling on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"I'd like to win a gold medal. I've been there twice before and
been disappointed twice before, so this will be a nice opportunity,
" said Armstrong in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Also on the team are Antonio Cruz, George Hincapie, Tyler
Hamilton and Fred Rodriguez, with Armstrong and Hamilton racing in
the individual time trial and all five in the road race.
</P>
<P>
Coach Jim Ochowicz hoped that the Americans should be medal
favorites, saying that "we are definitely going into Sydney with
one of the favorite teams on the road and probably the favorite in
the time-trial event."
</P>
<P>
While cycling remains largely unknown to most Americans,
Armstrong has become famous for his comeback from cancer to win
the Tour de France the last two years.
</P>
<P>
He was diagnosed with testicular cancer in October 1996,
shortly after placing sixth in the time trial and 12th in the road
race at the Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
He also rode in the 1992 Barcelona Olympics, finishing 14th in
the road race. 
</P>
</TEXT>
