<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, August 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI -- Finnish Foreign Minister Erkki Tumioja said Monday
that no attempt should be made to solve international conflicts
unilaterally without the authorization of international
organizations such as the United Nations and the Organization for
Security and Co-operation in Europe (OSCE).
</P>
<P>
Tumioja made the remarks at the Sixth World Congress for
Central and East European Studies held in Tampere, Finland, to
mark the 25th anniversary of the signature of the Helsinki Final
Act. The act, signed in 1975 by 35 countries including the United
States and the former Soviet Union, laid the foundation for what
later became the Vienna-based OSCE, which now groups 55 states of
Europe, Central Asia and North America. It is an important task
for the OSCE to ensure that international crises are solved
through multilateral actions in the first place, said Tumioja. (
Finland-OSCE Anniversary)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR -- The Federal Court of Malaysia Wednesday
dismissed an appeal by former deputy prime minister Anwar Ibrahim
against an earlier ruling by the High Court here that Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad need not testify at Anwar's sodomy trial.
</P>
<P>
A three-member panel led by Chief Justice Eusoff Chin made the
decision. Anwar, who discharged his seven counsel, made an
application himself Tuesday to disqualify the Chief Justice from
hearing his appeal, saying Eusoff could not be impartial because
of his relationships with the Prime Minister. His application was
dismissed by the court. (Malaysia-Anwar-Appeal)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- At least 18 laborers were massacred by militants
in Mir Bazar area of Anantnag district in west Kashmir late
Tuesday night, bringing the total death toll in militant attacks
on Tuesday in the region up to 48, the Press Trust of India (PTI)
reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A group of heavily armed militants descended on the residences
of the laborers and segregated the male members from women and
children and shot them after making them stand in a queue, the PTI
quoted local police as saying. The slaughter occurred at around 10
p.m. Tuesday, just four hours after another group of militants
attacked a pilgrim camp in Pahalgam town in west Kashmir, killing
30 people and injuring dozens of others. (India-Kashmir) 
</P>
</TEXT>
