<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Medical Experts Develop Effective Therapy for Pneumoconiosis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese medical experts have
developed an effective therapy of lungs lavage for curing the
fatal disease of pneumoconiosis, a typical occupational illness
threatening miners.
</P>
<P>
The therapy, which laves both lungs of a patient one and a half
hours, was developed by doctors with the Beidaihe Sanitarium of
Chinese Coal Miners in north China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 2,000 patients have been cured by the therapy, which the
doctors say is "effective and safe".
</P>
<P>
Medical workers could remove most of the dust in patients'
alveoluses and bronchuses.
</P>
<P>
China has about one million people suffering from
pneumoconiosis, accounting for half of the world's total.
</P>
<P>
The therapy has won a national award for technological
advancement.
</P>
<P>
Medical groups from Russia and the United States visited the
sanitarium, located in the famous Beidaihe summer resort, to seek
cooperation in the field.
</P>
<P>
In addition, medical experts in the sanitarium are exploring a
therapy to lave injurant in the lungs of chain-smokers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
