<HEADLINE> 18 Laborers Killed In Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A group of heavily armed militants descended on the residences
of the laborers and segregated the male members from women and
children and shot them after making them stand in a queue, the PTI
quoted local police as saying.
</P>
<P>
The slaughter occurred at around 10 p.m. Tuesday, just four
hours after another group of militants attacked a pilgrim camp in
Pahalgam town in west Kashmir, killing 30 people and injuring
dozens of others.
</P>
<P>
Although no militant group has so far claimed responsibility
for the two massacres, but officials in Kashmir believed that
those opposed to a ceasefire and possible peace talks between
Hizbul Mujahideen, a major militant outfit in Kashmir, and the
Indian government may be behind the attacks. The ceasefire deal,
reached during the last weekends, cast a hopeful light on the end
of violence in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
The slaughtered laborers, who worked in a brick kiln, were
mostly from the northern states of Uttar Pradesh, Madhya Pradesh
and Bihar, said the police.
</P>
<P>
The Indian government has condemned the massacres and said it
would continue its efforts to restore peace in Kashmir. 
</P>
