<DOCNO> XIE20000802.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ILO Moves to End Child Labor in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 2 (Xinhua) -- International Labor
Organization (ILO) Kathmandu has signed new agreements with a
partner organization in Nepal to renew its commitments to phase
out child labor in Nepal's carpet industry, ILO said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement signed Tuesday between ILO and National Society
for the Protection of Environment and Children (NASPEC) intends to
implement the consolidation phase of the action program entitled "
phasing out child labor from the carpet industries in Nepal", a
press release issued by ILO said.
</P>
<P>
The ultimate aim of this program is to make the carpet sector
free of child labor, it said.
</P>
<P>
Under the consolidation phase, 400 children working in the
carpet factories have been targeted for rehabilitation through the
action plan. Among them, 300 will be enrolled into formal schools
and 100 will be engaged in vocational training programs.
</P>
<P>
In the first three phases of the action program, NASPEC has
already rehabilitated 1,063 children from the carpet factories
through its Child Rehabilitation Center.
</P>
<P>
The center provided non-formal education, skill training,
counseling and health care to the rehabilitated children and
hundreds of children were reunited with their families and
enrolled into formal schools.
</P>
<P>
The action program also aims to develop a "code of conduct" for
the carpet manufacturers to prohibit child labor in their
establishments.
</P>
<P>
In collaboration with the Central Carpet Industries Association,
NASPEC will progressively phase out child labor from carpet
factories, which absorb a large portion of child laborers in Nepal.
It is estimated there are at least 2.5 million child laborers in
the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
