<HEADLINE> Pohang, Nippon Steel to Raise Mutual Share Ownership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 2 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's Pohang Iron and Steel
(POSCO) and Japan's Nippon Steel Corporation will invest 300
million U.S. dollars in each other to increase shares in mutual
ownership to 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
POSCO Chairman Yoo Sang-boo and Nippon Steel President Akira
Chihaya will meet in Tokyo next Tuesday to sign an agreement on
the investment, said POSCO Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement will cover increasing shares in mutual ownership
to 3 percent, a joint venture in a third nation, joint projects
for steel and iron development and cooperation in information
technology and research for new materials.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will also set up a joint venture in a third
nation to prevent overlapping investment and secure supplies to
automobile, shipping and electronics industries and to pursue
business projects in cyber space.
</P>
<P>
Now, POSCO owns 0.24 percent of Nippon Steel while the latter
owns 0.54 percent of the former.
</P>
<P>
POSCO ranked the first steel producer in the world with 26
million tons last year while Nippon Steel produced 24.33 million
tons. 
</P>
