<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkmen President Calls for Speeding up Afghan Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, August 2 (Xinhua)-- Turkmen President Saparmurad
Niyazov has expressed the hope that the peace process in the
neighboring Afghanistan would be accelerated to bring a final end
to 20 years of war there, said a Turkmen news agency report
monitored here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark Monday when he met with U.N. Secretary
General Kofi Annan's personal representative to Afghanistan,
Francesc Vendrell, the agency said in a dispatch from Ashkhabad,
capital of Turkmenistan.
</P>
<P>
Niyazov and Vendrell, who was on a mediation tour in the region,
exchanged views on the present situation in Afghanistan and
measures for quickening the process aimed at solving the Afghan
issue peacefully.
</P>
<P>
In the talks, Niyazov said that his country is earnestly hoping
for a paced up peace process in Afghanistan, where Islamic
fundamentalist group Taliban and the anti-Taliban group led by ex-
president Burhanuddin Rabbani have been fighting over the past few
years.
</P>
<P>
Early in July, the two warring sides fought two pitched battles
near the strategic Bagram airbase, 50 kilometers north of Kabul,
capital of Afghanistan, in which hundreds of solders from both
sides were killed.
</P>
<P>
The Turkmen president said that the conflicting parties in
Afghanistan have come to realize that they must create a peaceful
environment for the Afghan people.
</P>
<P>
Turkmenistan supports any peace effort as long as it is made in
light of respecting the choice of the Afghan people, he said.
</P>
<P>
Vendrell, whose views on the issue were not mentioned in the
report, came to Ashkhabad after a one-day stay in Kabul, where he
said that he hoped there will be no renewed fighting between the
two warring groups in the war-torn landlocked country.
</P>
<P>
If there is no more fighting, there is a greater chance for
peace, the U.N. mediator said.
</P>
<P>
His tour plan also included a visit to Uzbekistan and
Tajikistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
