<DOCNO> XIE20000802.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Anti-Crime Situation Improves in First Half Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The number of sizable offenses totaled 18,729 in the period, a
drop of 507 cases or 2.6 percent compared to the 19,236 cases
recorded in the same period of last year while the six-month crime
rate per 100,000 total population fell from 498 cases in the first
half of 1999 to 481 in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
The first half of this year saw significant declines in
property offenses such as snatch theft, robbery and housebreaking
which fell between 18 percent to 32 percent and offenses such as
murder, rape, rioting, motor vehicle theft, cheating and outraging
of modesty all declined with 27 murders and 63 cases of rape
recorded in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
Although snatch thefts and robberies committed on elderly
persons above 60 years old were down to 38 cases and 34 cases
respectively in the six months of 2000 from the 55 and 45 cases a
year ago, a higher number of juveniles were arrested for crimes in
the first half of 2000 increasing by 6.9 percent to 756 persons
compared to 707 persons in the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The number of foreigners arrested for crimes also decreased,
down 10.4 percent to 714 persons in the first six months of 2000
from 797 persons in the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The police attributed the anti-crime situation improvement
mainly to the strengthening of both intelligence and operations as
well as to public assistance.
</P>
<P>
The police said that four out 10 criminals involved in serious
offenses this year were caught with public assistance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
