<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wildfires Rage in Western U.S. States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. military Tuesday began
deploying soldiers to bolster firefighters who are battling with
stubborn wildfires that have consumed more than half-million acres
of timber, bush and brush in 10 western U.S. states, press reports
said.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 50 blazes have blackened more than 538,000 acres in
Arizona, California, Colorado, Idaho, Montana, Nevada, New Mexico,
Utah, Washington and Wyoming in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
With some 20,000 firefighters deployed in the western states,
the Pentagon ordered soldiers from Fort Hood, Texas, and Marines
from Camp Pendleton, Calif., to help the firefighters in the
coming days.
</P>
<P>
Michelle Barret, spokeswoman for the National Interagency Fire
Center in Boise, Idaho, said that about 500 soldiers were expected
to arrive in Idaho on Tuesday for on-the-job training while
another 500 Marines are expected to arrive Friday.
</P>
<P>
The largest wildfire in California, a 63,270-acre inferno in
Sequoia National Forest, was burning on the eastern side of the
Southern Sierra, 200 kilometers north of Los Angeles. There are
six wildfires still burning in the state.
</P>
<P>
In Idaho, 13 wildfires were burning, including the 77,000-acre
Salmon-Challis National Forest blaze. In southeast Idaho, the 850-
acre West Fork blaze, threatened 10 homes and 10 commercial
structures in Lava Hot Springs.
</P>
<P>
Montana firefighters battled nine fires, including a giant six-
blaze complex that has blackened 48,700 acres five miles (8
kilometers) east of Ashland in the southeast corner of the state.
</P>
<P>
In northeast Nevada, homes were threatened by the lightning-
caused 65,775-acre South Cricket grazing land fire 15 miles (24
kilometers) northeast of Wells. In the southeastern area, another
fire burning in 15,500 acres of pinion pine and juniper northeast
of Pioche, Nev., also threatened structures.
</P>
<P>
Experts point out that this is shaping up to be the worst fire
season since 1988, when 7.4 million acres were scorched nationwide.
</P>
<P>
"There were 2.2 million acres burned year-to-date in 1988.
We're already at 3.5 million and we're just coming into fire
season in most of the West," Barret said.
</P>
<P>
Fire experts also said it would be weeks before some of the
blazes are contained. Dry lightning forecast for Montana, Idaho,
Nevada and Oregon was expected to ignite even more fires.
</P>
<P>
Conditions were expected to remain unchanged for the next three
or four days and possibly more than a week, said Ed Waldapfel,
information officer for the fire center in Idaho.
</P>
<P>
"We're at the end of a La Nina weather event this year and
everything is critically dry," he said. "We've had virtually no
moisture this spring and summer. ... It's just a very combustible
situation." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000802.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Killed, Eight Injured In U.S. Mining Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Two workers were killed and
eight others injured Tuesday when a fire broke out and a methane
gas exploded in central Utah, a U.S. western state with a long
history of coal mining and mining tragedy.
</P>
<P>
One worker was in critical condition with burns and a head
injury, and another in serious condition with fractures and burns
from the blaze at the Willow Creek Mine, about 200 kilometers
southeast of Salt Lake City, according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
All 99 miners who were on duty at the time have been accounted
for and the cause of the fire was still undetermined, authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
Investigations suspect the fire started when the ceiling of
part of the mine shaft was allowed to collapse -- a normal part of
the mining operation, said Ron Spangler, a spokesman for mine
owner RAG Coal International of Essen, Germany.
</P>
<P>
But the roof collapse apparently created sparks that started a
fire and ignited a secondary explosion that may have been fueled
by a pocket of methane gas, Spangler said.
</P>
<P>
It was the mine's second serious fire in the past two years.
Methane ignited in November 1998, closing the mine for a year.
Forty-six miners escaped that fire unharmed, and safety officials
credited a system that uses pagers to alert miners of the danger.
</P>
<P>
Federal Mine Safety Health Administration investigators were on
the scene and a preliminary report was expected in several days.
</P>
<P>
The Willow Creek mine is a mining community of a county with a
long history of coal mining and mining tragedy.
</P>
<P>
One of the nation's worst mining disasters occurred 100 years
ago in nearby Scofield when more than 200 miners lost their lives.
Utah is one of the biggest coal producing states in U.S. West.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
