<DOCNO> XIE20000802.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Firms Eye Southern Africa for More Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The political environment in these two countries is conducive
to investment, Thailand's Ambassador to South Africa, Bandhit
Sotipalalit, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Bandhit led a delegation to the two countries between July 22
to 31 as part of the government's efforts to strengthen trade and
investment in the region.
</P>
<P>
Delegation member, a senior executive of Thailand's biggest
agro-industrial conglomerate Charoen Pokphand (CP), was quoted by
the paper as saying that Namibia has great potential for chicken
farming due to its close proximity to major markets.
</P>
<P>
CP has been looking for investment opportunities for some time,
as it first opened an office in South Africa six years ago and has
captured 80 percent of the frozen chicken market.
</P>
<P>
New investment will add value to the company's local activities
by cutting out transport costs and create jobs for local people.
</P>
<P>
Thai Chamber of Commerce director Olan Viravan was quoted as
saying that Thai textile and garment firms, faced with excess
capacity because of export quota restrictions imposed by the
United States and the European Union, could relocate part of their
operations to Namibia and Botswana, where they can take advantage
of SADC's trade privileges.
</P>
<P>
Incentives provided by the Botswana government to foreign
investors, such as labor cost rebates for the first five years,
are very attractive, he added.
</P>
<P>
Namibia and Botswana each has a population of less than two
million, but both are members of the SADC, the regional group of
14 countries with a total population of 194 million and a combined
gross domestic product of 170 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
