<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Conflicts Should be Settled Through International Organizations, Says Finnish FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, August 1 (Xinhua) - Finnish Foreign Minister Erkki
Tumioja said Monday that no attempt should be made to solve
international conflicts unilaterally without the authorization of
international organizations such as the United Nations and the
Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe (OSCE).
</P>
<P>
Tumioja made the remarks at the Sixth World Congress for
Central and East European Studies held in Tampere, Finland, to
mark the 25th anniversary of the signature of the Helsinki Final
Act.
</P>
<P>
The act, signed in 1975 by 35 countries including the United
States and the former Soviet Union, laid the foundation for what
later became the Vienna-based OSCE, which now groups 55 states of
Europe, Central Asia and North America.
</P>
<P>
It is an important task for the OSCE to ensure that
international crises are solved through multilateral actions in
the first place, said Tumioja.
</P>
<P>
Multilateral action is much better than unilateral action and
could possibly be the only sustainable approach that can settle
international conflicts, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Such multilateral action would involve all parties concerned,
provide transparency to the settlement, increase the respect for
international law and reduce the dangers of using force, he said.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the OSCE, the United Nations and the European
Union will strengthen cooperation so as to prevent and control
crises effectively. He held that the situation in the Balkans has
exposed the weakness of the international community in controlling
crises.
</P>
<P>
More than 2,000 scholars from more than 40 countries attended
the congress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000802.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Landslides in Brazil leave at Least 20 Dead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Landslides caused by heavy rains
have killed at least 20 people and left thousands homeless in
northeast Brazil, authorities said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Downpour starting Saturday and continuing through Tuesday has
already caused more than 100 landslides which have affected Recife,
capital of the state of Pernambuco, and neighboring cities.
</P>
<P>
Lots of shops, schools and other public buildings as well as
hospitals had been shut down Monday, and Pernambuco has been
declared a state of emergency.
</P>
<P>
Since the climate phenomenon will continue for over 48 hours,
which means more problems and deaths, authorities recommend people
to take necessary precautions against the rainstorm said to be the
worst in the past 40 years in the area.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian President Fernando Enrique Cardoso has ordered the
army to take part in the rescue work.
</P>
<P>
At Recife, with over 1.35 million inhabitants, more than 1,000
people have had to leave their houses, most of them located in the
city's outskirts. Rescue teams are fighting against heavy downpour
to withdraw victims from the destroyed houses.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
