<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pipeline Burst Causes Slick in British Columbia, Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The pipeline running between
Taylor and Prince George in Canada's British Columbia burst early
Tuesday to form a 21-kilometer-long slick into the Pine River in
the northeastern part of the province.
</P>
<P>
The provincial Environment Ministry confirmed later in the day
that up to 10,000 barrels of crude oil spilled into the river to
threaten the water supply of Chetwynd, about 100 kilometers
downstream from the pipeline break.
</P>
<P>
The pipeline was shut off after the spill was detected, while
booms were set along the river from the town of 4,000 people to
contain the oil.
</P>
<P>
More than 70 workers are skimming oil off the river and pumping
it into trucks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chetwynd Mayor Charlie Lasser declared "severe water
restrictions" to ensure that the town's water reserves could last
four to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
Authorities have not yet determined what caused the break of
the pipeline, which belongs to the Calgary-based Pembina Pipeline
Corp.
</P>
<P>
A rain storm was reported Monday night to cause power outages
and shut down some pumps in the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
