<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Changes Northern Military Command Structure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Island newspaper reported that the position of Senior Naval
Officer Commanding Northern Naval Operations held by Rear Admiral
H.R. Amaraweera has been scrapped with Amaraweera being
transferred to the navy headquarters in Colombo as Director of
Naval Administration.
</P>
<P>
With the scrapping of the post, Commander of Northern Naval
Area Commodore S.P. Weerasekera has been made the navy's top man
in the north. However, he has also been transferred and replaced
by Rear Admiral W.K.J. Karannagoda, who has just returned after a
year's training in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The latest command change follows last week's scrapping of the
position of overall Operations Commander of the North, which was
held by Major General Janaka Perera since March. Perera has been
transferred to the army headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Military sources said the government's move was in response to
the stabilizing situation in Jaffna peninsula.
</P>
<P>
However, the separatist Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE)
rebels, fighting for a separate state in Sri Lanka's north and
east since 1983, are reportedly planning for a major assault on
the government troops deployed in the Jaffna peninsula.
</P>
<P>
After ferocious fighting in April and May in the Jaffna
peninsula, a lull in the fighting ensued but analysts see it as
simply the calm before the storm. Government troops and LTTE
rebels have cashed in on the lull to prepare for war and a
showdown is on the cards.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has launched a massive recruit drive and the latest
batch of recruits believed to number over 1,000 are expected to be
battle-ready by mid-August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000802.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Govt to Launch Strategies to Ease Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The strategies, aimed to lift 9.9 million Thais above the
poverty line over the next six years, were adopted at a meeting of
the Ministerial Council on Social Policy early this week, which
was chaired by Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The short and medium-term strategies would involve the
development of occupational knowledge and skill for the poor,
promotion of self-sufficiency economy and community empowerment,
improvement of social welfare and fundamental service for the poor,
and greater investment in human and natural resources, it
described.
</P>
<P>
For the long-term strategies, they would involve reforms of
economic and social mechanisms, as well as of natural resource
management and laws to promote the rights and social empowerment
of the poor, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Government agencies and parties concerned are required to put
the short and medium strategies into action by the year 2002, the
beginning of the country's Ninth National Economic and Social
Development Plan, according to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
