<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thirty Killed in Kashmir Massacre by Militants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the first major attack on pilgrims in Kashmir, militants
fired indiscriminately on the pilgrims at the camp at around 6 p.m.
Tuesday, killing eight of them on the spot and injuring 20 others,
the PTI had reported late Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers on Wednesday morning, however, put the
casualties much higher than the PTI report. AT least 23 people
were feared killed and 70 others injured, said the Indian Express,
adding that the dead included at least a dozen pilgrims, and local
shopkeepers and porters who were camping there at the service of
the pilgrims. The Hindu put the death toll at 27.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest PTI report, the death toll in Tuesday's
attack had risen to 30 as eight more people succumbed to injuries
in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee and Home Affairs
Minister L.K. Advani condemned the massacre and required necessary
measures to be taken to provide adequate security for the pilgrims.
There are currently 10,000 to 12,000 pilgrims in Pahalgam, who are
heading for the holy Amarnath Cave for pilgrimage, said the PTI.
</P>
<P>
Advani also asserted that the Indian government's efforts for
restoring peace in Jammu and Kashmir would continue.
</P>
<P>
"It seems that some of the militants are frightened of
prospects of peace and chose these innocent pilgrims as soft
targets. It is a desperate act and it only proves that the
government is proceeding on the right track," Advani was quoted as
saying by the Hindu.
</P>
<P>
On last Saturday, Hizbul Mujahideen, a major militant outfit in
the Kashmir valley, offered a unilateral ceasefire, to which the
Indian government responded with a cessation of all military
operations against Hizbul Mujahideen and an offer of peace talks
with the militant group. On Tuesday Hizbul Mujahideen named its
negotiator. All these have brought about hope for an end of
bloodshed in Kashmir, which has been haunted by militancy for a
decade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
