<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Newsprint Prices Go Up: Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The newsprint prices are expected
to go up further in the second half of this year, boosted by
rising material costs and increasing domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
Two newsprint makers in north China announced a raise in prices
by 10 percent on Tuesday, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The price was pushed up to around 6,000 yuan per ton Tuesday,
according to sources with the two firms in north China's Jilin and
Qiqiha'er.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made just after newsprint makers in south
China's Yibin, Guangzhou and Yueyang raised their prices to about
5,800 yuan in June and July this year.
</P>
<P>
"We have given newsprint makers freedom to adjust their prices
according to the market demand," said Zhao Wei with the China
Association of Papermaking Industries.
</P>
<P>
Zhao said the price hike is reasonable and expected. "Cost for
newsprint makers have been rising as prices for papermaking
materials on the domestic and overseas markets have surged."
</P>
<P>
China is expected to use 1.6 million tons of newsprint this
year, compared with 1.4 million last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
