<DOCNO> XIE20000802.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Soldier Given Life Sentence For Killing Girl in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, August 1 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. soldier on Tuesday was
sentenced to  imprisonment for life without parole for the murder
of an 11-year-old Kosovo Albanian girl.
</P>
<P>
An American military court based in southern German city of
Wuerzburg handed down the maximum sentence on Staff Sgt. Frank
Ronghi, 36, who was found guilty of raping and murdering the girl,
Merita Shabiu, in mid-January this year, while he was on
peacekeeping duty in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Merita was raped and murdered in the basement of a house near
the town of Vitina, and her bruised and slashed body was found in
the snow outside the town on January 13.
</P>
<P>
According to the DPA, the German News Agency, there was
evidence that Ronghi had planned the raping and killing. Ronghi
had told his comrades he had a plan to "grab a little girl and
rape her, but would have to kill her to cover up the crime and
shift the blame to the Serbs," the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
In testimony, prosecutors detailed how Ronghi lured the girl
into the basement, where he raped her and killed her to stop her
cries. He went back for the body later, stuffed under a stairway
in two U.N. flour sacks, and buried it beneath the snow on a
hilltop, according to other media reports.
</P>
<P>
His sentence is the most severe one available to the American
military court in Germany, where the death penalty does not exist.
</P>
<P>
Ronghi, from the U.S. State of Ohio, was a weapons squad leader
assigned to the 3rd Battalion, 504th Parachute Infantry Regiment
in North Carolina. He was sent to Kosovo last summer.
</P>
<P>
Media reports quoted Ronghi as saying: "I don't know what went
wrong that day. I apologize from the bottom of my heart to the
family. I ask them for forgiveness."
</P>
<P>
The girl's father, Hamdi Shabiu, told reporters that while the
family was satisfied with the verdict and the U.S. Army's handling
of the case, they would never be able to forgive Ronghi.
</P>
<P>
"If he had accidentally killed her, we would forgive him on the
spot. But not only did he do what he did to her, he wanted to
hide her body, so that we would not even have a grave for her," he
was quoted as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000802.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zickler's Hat-trick Lifts Bayern to German League Cup Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, August 1 (Xinhua) -- A hat-trick by striker Alexander
Zickler helped Bayern Munich to a 5-1 win over Hertha Berlin on
Tuesday for another German League Cup title.
</P>
<P>
This is Bayern's fourth consecutive final victory in the
tournament for the top six finishers of last season.
</P>
<P>
Zickler gave Bayern a 1-0 lead with a shot from the corner of
the box in the 50th minute.
</P>
<P>
Three minutes later, fellow striker Carsten Jancker increased
the lead with a deflected shot from just outside the penalty area.
</P>
<P>
Iceland defender Eyjolfur Sverrisson put Hertha 3-0 down with
an own goal under pressure from new Bayern signing Ciriaco Sforza
in the 57th minute.
</P>
<P>
Striker Kai Michalke restored hope for the Berlin club by
pulling one back in the 61st minute, but Bayern hit back soon and
Zickler scored his second goal with a swift counter-attack in the
67th minute.
</P>
<P>
Zickler finished his hat-trick when there remained five minutes
to go.
</P>
<P>
The German champions will meet Hertha again when the Bundesliga
resumes on August 12. 
</P>
</TEXT>
