<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jones Wins 100 meters in Stockholm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Marion Jones of the United
States o'clocked a wind-assisted 10.68 seconds to win the women's
100 meters race at an international athletics meeting here on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Finally I have broken the 10.70 barrier. I couldn't be more
pleased," said Jones.
</P>
<P>
The wind speed was 2.2 meters a second, according to the
organizers.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old is aiming to became the first athlete to win
five Olympic golds as she is to compete in the 100 meters, 200
meters, long jump and both relays at Sydney. On Tuesday she
described her Olympic challenge as "a realistic goal I know I can
achieve."
</P>
<P>
In the night's other events, Trinidadian Ato Boldon won a tight
100 meters in 10.01 seconds. Second-placed Obadele Thomson of
Barbados clocked the same time.
</P>
<P>
Canada's reigning Olympic champion Donovan Bailey trailed in a
miserable seventh, clocking a poor 10.27 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Olympic 110 meters hurdles champion Allen Johnson, who went
under 13 seconds for the first time in two years at the U.S.
Olympic trials in Sacramento two weeks ago, won his event in 13.15
seconds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
