<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Say Genes Can Cause Nerve Center Malfunctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have found out
that the activities of animal's nerve center are controlled by
certain genes.
</P>
<P>
A group of scientists from the No.4 Military Medical College in
this capital of northwest province of Shaanxi announced that they
have recorded nerve center malfunctions of a mouse after they
eliminated some genes from its genome.
</P>
<P>
The mouse soon died of brain hydropsy and hydrocele accompanied
with the death of a large number of nerve cells and a massive
transformation of never center, showing that the eliminated genes
had participated in the growth of the animal's nerve center.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that human beings identified genes
relating to the growth and functions of nerve center, according to
Professor Han Hua, who led the research group.
</P>
<P>
The malfunctions of nerve center can result in dementia among
the aged people and other serious nerve diseases. The scientists
believed that the breakthrough would help find out ways to cure
the diseases.
</P>
<P>
The scientists also discovered in a separate experiment that
the elimination of certain genes can cause arthritis and lymph
diseases.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000802.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Further Liberalize Auto Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 2 (Xinhua) -- China is considering to further
liberalize the auto sector to prepare for the imminent entry into
the World Trade Organization (WTO), according to a front-page
story on "China Materials News".
</P>
<P>
Related departments disclosed that China will further abolish
restrictions on the sector to allow auto makers to manufacture all
varieties of automobiles and auto products and liberalize prices
on the car market.
</P>
<P>
Auto producers are encouraged to merge to promote scale
production in order to lower costs and enhance efficiency.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, China is also considering to stop levying irrational
taxes, such as consumption tax imposed on auto factories and
license tax imposed on car-purchasers.
</P>
<P>
In recent months, a price war has been raging across the
country as a number of auto makers slashed their prices to promote
sales.
</P>
<P>
The Dongfeng-Citroen Automobile Co Ltd based in Wuhan, capital
of central China's Hubei Province, announced that it will cut the
price of its Fukang cars by 6,000 yuan (722.9 US dollars) to 15,
200 (1,831.3 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The unexpected announcement came just days after the company
said that it does not plan to follow Shanghai Volkswagen, which
cut the price of its Santana 2000 by more than 10,000 yuan (1200 U.
S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Jetta, a Changchun-produced Volkswagen model and Xiali,
produced in Tianjin, will be very likely to follow suit in the
near future.
</P>
<P>
Industry observers commented that even though China will loosen
control on the sector and auto makers will try every means to sell
their products, consumers are still very cautious on buying cars.
</P>
<P>
Price cuts have not stirred up a wave of purchasing as many had
expected. Insiders said that price cuts will continue in the short
term.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
