<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are the economic
briefs from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Arab Trade Financing Program (ATFP) said on
Wednesday it had signed a 40 million U.S. Dollar line of credit
with Moroccan Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Dhabi-based ATFP comment that the line of credit signed
on Tuesday would finance a variety of trade deals between Morocco
and other Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
The agreement would bring to 24 the number of credit line deals
extended to Morocco, worth a total of 333 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The United Arab Emirates' Federal Environmental
Agency (FEA) has drafted regulations for management of medical and
hazardous wastes in the country.
</P>
<P>
The regulations, after approval, will be incorporated into the
executive order of the Federal Law No.24 of 1999 on protection and
development of environment, according to Dr Salim Masri Al Dhahiri,
director general of the Agency.
</P>
<P>
He said the draft comprising 15 articles specifies the
authorities which will issue licences for each type of hazardous
and medical waste and explains procedures and terms and conditions
to be followed to obtain a licence or to import hazardous chemical
materials.
</P>
<P>
The draft specifies general regulations and measures for
management of hazardous wastes, including collection, storage,
transport and disposal. Another section highlights general
regulations and measures for management of medical wastes.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Construction of two district cooling plants at the
Zayed Military city in Abu Dhabi is to commence this week following
the signing of the contract between domestic and foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
The 40-million-dollar project, the second phase of the Zayed
Military City, includes the construction of two new plants, which
will produce 20,000 refrigerating tons per day to a total area of
12 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The project is expected to be completed at the end of 2001.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The United Arab Emirates Offsets Group (UOG) has
set up a new company to supervise the development of the Dolphin
gas initiative.
</P>
<P>
The new company will oversee the development of the multi-
billion dollar Dophin gas project of the UOG.
</P>
<P>
The UOG holds a 51 percent stake in the new company. 
</P>
</TEXT>
