<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worldwide DVD Player Market to Expand This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Driven by the launch of DVD-
based games consoles, this year's worldwide market of DVD players
will experience a big expansion, with shipments hitting 22 million
units, according to a new research released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Retail revenues across the three major markets of the United
States, Europe and Japan will rise by 220 percent from last year
to reach 7 billion U.S. dollars, said U.S. market researcher
Strategy Analytics in the research report.
</P>
<P>
According to the research, DVD will become the standard home
video format within five years, largely replacing VHS cassettes.
DVD video disc shipments this year will reach nearly 400 million
units worldwide, and continue to soar to 2.3 billion by 2005,
worth 44 billion dollars. Including other DVD formats such as
games, ROM and audio, shipments will reach 3.7 billion units by
2005, worth nearly 100 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Rising hardware sales are being offset by falling prices, said
the research firm, adding that Chinese-sourced players in
particular are having a noticeable impact.
</P>
<P>
"The content industry will ultimately benefit the most from DVD
's success," said the report. "Manufacturers will continue to
suffer from falling prices and declining margins, but DVD's
superiority will tempt many consumers to buy more video and to
replace their existing VHS collections."
</P>
<P>
Overall consumer sales of DVD devices will reach 46 million
units this year, including 21 million in the U.S. and 17 million
in Europe. Basic DVD players will account for two-thirds of set-
top shipments in 2000, the remainder being DVD games consoles,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 2000, the report said, 14 percent of U.S. and 5
percent of European homes will own at least one TV-based DVD
player. In addition, many homes are acquiring DVD-capable PCs, so
that overall household access to DVD is 25 percent in the U.S. and
14 percent in Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000802.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands Strike Again At San Francisco Hospitals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The strike, the latest in a string of labor problems to hit San
Francisco hospitals, involved more than 3,500 employees
represented by the Service Employees International Union, ranging
from licensed vocational nurses to laboratory technicians,
secretaries, housekeepers and food service aides.
</P>
<P>
"Management of the multibillion dollar corporations will not
allow workers to have a real voice in decisions about staffing
levels and is refusing to ensure a stable and experienced
workforce to care for patients," the union said in a statement
announcing the strike.
</P>
<P>
The union said it was unable to reach an agreement with Sutter
Health, which operates five of the affected hospitals, and
Catholic Healthcare West, which operates three. Catholic
Healthcare West had left the bargaining table last Thursday, and
Sutter left Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
The workers struck at 6 a.m. Wednesday and plan to walk picket
lines for 48 hours. Some of the hospitals plan to cut the number
of patients or canceled some elective surgeries.
</P>
<P>
The sticking point for the union is staffing. Union members say
they want a voice in determining staffing levels, which they say
are too low.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman Robert Polzoni said Catholic Healthcare West had
offered a 12 percent raise over four years to the workers. He said
the union's demands amount to a 24 percent raise the first year,
which he called "outrageous." Management also called the union's
desire for lifetime job guarantees unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
Hospital officials said they had taken steps to minimize the
impact of the work stoppage, and hoped it would not be necessary
to reschedule elective surgeries or move patients.
</P>
<P>
The two-day strike follows a one-day stoppage at many of the
same hospitals early last month. About 4,000 union members staged
a one-day strike July 6 at the eight hospitals, as well as two
independents, forcing many facilities to transfer patients, hire
replacement workers and cancel elective surgeries.
</P>
<P>
Labor problems have hit other local hospitals as well. Late
last month, about 1,700 nurses from the Stanford Medical Center
and Lucile Packard Children's Hospital ended a 50-day strike and
agreed to a contract providing a 10 percent pay hike over two
years.
</P>
<P>
At an Oakland hospital, a handful of anesthesiologists recently
quit their jobs in a protest over work conditions and pay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000802.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British MPs Urge Caution on U.S. Anti-Missile Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 2 (Xinhua) -- A group of British members of
parliament (MPs) Wednesday urged the government to try and steer
the United States away from its National Missile Defense (NMD)
plan.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Affairs Select Committee in the House of Commons, a
cross-party group of MPs, said in a report that the U.S. plan is
inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
"We are not convinced that the U.S. plans to deploy NMD
represent an appropriate response to the proliferation problems
faced by the international community," the committee said in the
report.
</P>
<P>
"We recommend that the government encourage the USA to seek
other ways of reducing the threat it perceives," the report said.
</P>
<P>
In a scheme fiercely opposed by China and Russia, the United
States said the NMD would offer some defense against "rogue"
states with nuclear capability.
</P>
<P>
But after two of the three U.S. experiments to shoot down
missiles over the Pacific have failed, there have been growing
calls in the U.S. Congress and from national security specialists
for President Bill Clinton to delay making a decision on deploying
the controversial 60 billion U.S. dollar system.
</P>
<P>
Britain is in a sensitive position because the first phase of
the U.S. plan requires an upgrading of a strategic radar base at
Fylingdales in Yorkshire, northern England.
</P>
<P>
The British government says it has had no direct request from
the U.S. and so does not have to make a decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
