<DOCNO> XIE20000802.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain to Fingerprint Immigrants, Asylum Seekers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 2 (Xinhua) -- British Home Office (interior
ministry) announced on Wednesday plans to introduce new system of
taking and storing fingerprints of asylum seekers coming into the
country, aiming to "clamp down on abuse" of immigration rules.
</P>
<P>
The new system,under which automated fingerprinting equipment
will be set up at immigration and asylum screening units, would
allow information to be shared with Britain's European partners,
the Home Office said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The system is to be introduced in Britain in two phases, the
first scheduled to be complete by December this year and the
second by March 2001.
</P>
<P>
The new sysytem will speed up the processing of immigration
cases and improve detection of multipile applications, initially
within Britain, and longer term across the European Union.
</P>
<P>
It will also feed into Eurodac, a planned EU central database
to contain fingerprints of asylum applicants and certain other
third-country nationals.
</P>
<P>
The Home Office said the new fingerprinting system would force
EU member countries to take responsibility for illegal immigrants
they find and to discourage "asylum shopping" --where potential
immigrants go from state to state trying to get in.
</P>
<P>
"The automated fingerprint identification system will help us
to cooperate with other European countries to tackle illegal
immigration effectively," said Immigration Minister Barbara Roche
as the plan was announced.
</P>
<P>
She said Britain had "a long tradition of providing refuge to
those fleeing persecution" but added: "We are determined to clamp
down on abuse of the system."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000802.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> L.American Balance of Payments Deficit To Be 50 BLn Dlrs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The current account deficit of
the balance of payments of Latin America and the Caribbean will be
some 50 billion dollars by the end of 2000, similar to that of
the previous year, according to a study made by the Latin America
and the Caribbean Economic Commission (CEPAL).
</P>
<P>
The study published Wednesday here said that the current
account deficit of the balance of payments will increase this year
in Colombia, Mexico and some Central American countries, while
Chile will have a moderate deficit after an equilibrated result in
1999.
</P>
<P>
Other countries will not register important variances, or will
have a lesser deficit than in the previous year, as in the case of
Argentina, Brazil and Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
The regional deficit reduced variance will be the result of two
counteracting trends: the recovery of the growth rate of imports
associated to the reactivation of the activity, which reverted the
1999 drop, and a strong expansion in the value of exports,
attributed to the growth of the volumes and to the recovery of the
prices of many basic products, especially those of raw materials.
</P>
<P>
The region will show, for the first time since 1997 and the
start of the global crisis, a positive global result of the
balance of payments, and will not have to recur to reserves to
cover the deficit.
</P>
<P>
Foreign trade shows a clear upward trend, recovering after the
1999 drop. This recovery was attributed as much to the factors
that determine the prices of the exported products, as to the
world and regional economic activity.
</P>
<P>
The economies' reactivation resulted also in a significant
increase of imports.
</P>
<P>
The CEPAL said that the world economic activity accelerated in
comparison to last year's, promoting the foreign demand of the
products of the region. The growth was especially rapid in the
United States, which benefited Mexico and the Central American and
Caribbean countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
