<DOCNO> XIE20000802.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Expresses Concern on U.S. NMD Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Britain said Wednesday that it is
concerned about the United States' National Missile Defense (NMD)
plan.
</P>
<P>
Following the publication of a British report on weapons of
mass destruction, prepared by a special committee in the House of
Commons, Foreign Office Minister Peter Hain said Britain would
continue to make clear Britain's concern in discussions with the
United States.
</P>
<P>
"We continue to make clear to the U.S. in discussing our own
concerns," Hain said in a statement issued Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We agree that the Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty (ABMT) should
be preserved," Hain said.
</P>
<P>
In the report, the Foreign Affairs Select Committee, a cross-
party group in the parliament, said that the U.S. NMD plan is
inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
"We are not convinced that the U.S. plans to deploy NMD
represent an appropriate response to the proliferation problems
faced by the international community," said the report.
</P>
<P>
The report also recommended British government to encourage the
U.S. to seek other ways of reducing the threat it perceives.
</P>
<P>
In a scheme fiercely opposed by China and Russia, the United
States said the NMD would offer some defense against "rogue"
states with nuclear capability.
</P>
<P>
But after two of the three U.S. experiments to shoot down
missiles over the Pacific have failed, there have been growing
calls, both from the U.S. and other countries, for President Bill
Clinton to delay making a decision on deploying the controversial
system, which will cost about 60 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Britain is in a sensitive position because the first phase of
the U.S. plan requires an upgrading of a strategic radar base at
Fylingdales in Yorkshire, northern England. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
