<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FORATOM Welcomes French Choice of Nuclear Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 2 (Xinhua) -- European Atomic Forum (FORATOM)
said here Wednesday it welcomes a conclusion by a study for the
French government that nuclear power is likely to retain its
economic viability in France over the next 50 years.
</P>
<P>
The Brussels-based trade association for the European nuclear
industry said the French report concluded that existing nuclear
power stations should retain their cost advantage over gas-fired
plants,provided they are not closed down prematurely, and that
nuclear is likely to retain its economic edge when it comes to
building new generating capacity.
</P>
<P>
The 288-page report compiled for French Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin, covering the period up to 2050, was produced by senior
officials from three separate organizations - a key public policy-
making forum, France's national scientific research center and
French atomic energy commission.
</P>
<P>
France started its major nuclear power program after the oil
crisis in early 1970s. Now, about three-quarters of electricity is
nuclear generated in France.
</P>
<P>
The authors of the report have stressed that their study is not
designed as a guide for policy-makers or an attempt to influence
public opinion, but provides technical, economic and ecological
information needed for a public debate on France's energy options
in the future.
</P>
<P>
"The French example now also shows that nuclear can maintain
its cost competitiveness, even when there is the attraction of low
gas prices. The new study demonstrates that nuclear is a viable
and desirable option in terms of both hard cash and environmental
protection," said FORATOM's Secretary General Wolf J. Schmidt-
Kuster.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
