<HEADLINE> Former U.S President Ford Suffers Mild Strokes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHILADELPHIA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Former U.S. President Gerald
Ford was hospitalized Wednesday with slurred speech, dizziness and
arm weakness after suffering two small strokes during the
Republican national convention.
</P>
<P>
Doctors said the 87-year-old former president appeared to
suffer no brain damage or permanent disability and chances for a
full recovery were good.
</P>
<P>
The former president was in stable condition and his wife Betty
Ford was by his side. Ford walked into Hahnemann University
Hospital under his own power, doctors said.
</P>
<P>
"His thinking is perfect," said Dr. Robert Schwartzman, chief
of neurology at the hospital. "He'll have to be on medication but
I think he'll do very well."
</P>
<P>
Ford, America's 38th president, was saluted by the Republicans
at the national convention Tuesday night for his services during
his term.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton spoke with Mrs. Ford by telephone and
expressed his concern. Texas Governor George W. Bush, who arrived
Wednesday morning in Philadelphia to accept the Republican
presidential nomination, also spoke to Mrs. Ford by telephone and
conveyed "his prayers and love."
</P>
<P>
Ford was appointed vice president by Richard Nixon, and sworn
in as president in August 1974 after Nixon's resignation in the
midst of the Watergate scandal. He was defeated in the
presidential election in 1976 by Jimmy Carter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
