<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Remains Moldova's Number One Economic Partner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Russia remains the number one
economic partner of Moldova in spite of the latter's pledges to
turn to Western markets.
</P>
<P>
The former Soviet republic in the first half of this year
exported goods worth 94 million U.S. dollars (42 percent of the
total) to Russia, 22 million dollars more than those in the same
period of last year, the Moldovan Basa-press news agency reported
Wednesday, quoting sources of the Economics and Reforms Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine comes next with 19 million dollars worth of Moldovan
imports absorbed; Germany and Italy rank the third with 16 million
dollars each; and Romania imported Moldovan goods worth 14 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the ministry said the exports to Romania
dropped two-three-fold compared with the previous years.
</P>
<P>
Romania is the number one country in terms of imports, with
Moldova absorbing goods worth 60.8 million dollars; Russia
accounted for 60.7 million dollars of Moldovan imports; Ukraine
for 48 million and Germany for 32 million.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months of this year, Moldova registered a 125.
7 million-dollar trade deficit, or 72.7 million dollars up from
last year's similar period.
</P>
<P>
The country's foreign trade valued a total of 563 million
dollars in the first half of the year, of which the imports
amounted to 344.4 million.
</P>
<P>
An increase in exports was behind a 24.7 percent increase in
the trade with Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) countries.
The trade with other countries rose by 36.5 percent because of
imports.
</P>
<P>
Moldova's main exports are food and wine while imports are
equipment and electronic products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
