<HEADLINE> Colombian Official Defends Neutral Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Colombia's High Commissioner for
Peace Camilo Gomez Alzate defended Wednesday the neutral zone as a
mechanism for peace talks with the Revolutionary Armed Forces of
Colombia (FARC).
</P>
<P>
Gomez took part in a discussion in the Senate about the 42,000
square kilometer neutral zone established at the end of 1998 in
the south of the country, where many charges of human rights
violations by the guerrilla have been made.
</P>
<P>
He said that the creation of the neutral zone not only has
facilitated dialogue and generated confidence between the parts,
but has also made it possible for the parts to discuss the
possibility of a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
With some 17,000 members, the FARC is the biggest insurgent
force in the country.
</P>
<P>
"We have entered a stage in which I expect concrete agreements
in a short time that will permit advance in the discussion of the
agenda and of the cease-fire and the end of the hostilities," said
the commissioner.
</P>
<P>
Gomez Alzate said that it is necessary to make "prudent and
discrete" the discussion of a truce to avoid frustrating the
citizens' expectations. 
