<HEADLINE> More Rwandan Refugees in Tanzania Register for Repatriation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 3 (Xinhua) -- More Rwandan refugees in Imbuba
and Rukore camps in Tanzania have voluntarily registered for
repatriation despite threats from those who refuse to return home,
Rwanda News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Registration for repatriation is made secretly because camp
leaders and other Rwandans who do not want to return home threaten
to harass and kill those intending to voluntarily return home," a
returnee was quoted as saying in Rwanda's southeastern town of
Kibungo at the Rwanda-Tanzania border.
</P>
<P>
According to Eugene Barikana, Prefect of Kibungo Prefecture,
the major reason that has led people to flee Rwanda is rumors that
have circulated alleging that the Tutsi are planning a genocide-
like revenge on the Hutu population.
</P>
<P>
Sixty refugees have willingly returned home in two weeks time
following government efforts to sensitize all refugees to return
home.
</P>
<P>
More have been repatriated from the Democratic Republic of the
Congo. 
</P>
