<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Intensifies Efforts to Help Relieve Drought Victims in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The Kenya Country Office of the
United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) has accelerated and
intensified programs to prevent vulnerable children and women in
drought-hit areas in Kenya from falling victims of infectious and
waterborne diseases.
</P>
<P>
The office said in a statement here on Thursday that the agency
is pre-positioning essential drugs, water purification materials,
water equipment and parts, and supplementary food in Turkana, one
of the most affected districts in northwestern Kenya.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF has shipped a consignment of 211 cartons of drugs worth
more than 3,200 U.S. dollars for combating a cholera outbreak in
Kisumu district in southwestern Kenya, the office said, adding
that emergency health kits and medical equipment valued at about
84,000 dollars have been dispatched to district hospitals in 19
drought-hit districts.
</P>
<P>
Since the onset of the drought later last year, UNICEF has
supplied a total of 900 tons of food at a cost of 404,100 dollars
to Turkana and Marsabit districts in northern Kenya.
</P>
<P>
At the request of the European Union, the office said, the
agency's water and nutrition experts participated in a assessment
mission to three drought-hit districts, and one of the findings by
the mission is the need to increase supplementary feeding for
children in pre-primary schools.
</P>
<P>
In the water and sanitation sector, the agency said it is
currently installing boreholes and swallow well pumps in more than
50 water supply points in Turkana and other districts, and
supporting maintenance of boreholes in pastoral areas in northern
and northeastern Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The office noted that UNICEF is now supporting a 21-million-
shillings (about 280,000 dollars) multiple indicator cluster
survey to 9,000 households in 50 districts in the country to
generate new data on child survival, development and protection,
and other indicators including infant and maternal well-being.
</P>
<P>
The data is expected to be documented at the end of October
this year, the agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
