</P>
<P>
Arafat is also to hold talks with South African President Thabo
Mbeki and former president Nelson Mandela, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader earlier on Thursday told journalists
when he arrived at Waterkloof Airforce base in Pretoria that he
wants Mandela to mediate in the Middle East peace talks and he has
envisaged a particular role for the former South African president.
</P>
<P>
This is not the first time that Arafat asked Mandela to assist.
</P>
<P>
However, Mandela is still mediating in the Burundi peace
process and has expressed several times that he does not plan to
become directly involved in the Middle East peace talks.
</P>
<P>
After the failed U.S.-brokered peace talks last month between
Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak in Camp David, the
Palestinian leader is again seeking support from his allies to his
strong position of unilaterally declaring a Palestinian statehood
on September 13 even if there was no peace accord by then.
</P>
<P>
Arafat previously paid a five-day visit to France and several
Arab states, including Egypt, during which he briefed the leaders
on the latest Camp David talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
