<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Denies Attacks on Eritrean Civilians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia has categorically
denied an allegation by the Eritrean side that its troops attacked
Eritreans on the border.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian government spokesperson's office said in a
statement Wednesday evening that the Ethiopian army, which is now
in control of Senafe and its surrounding areas, was in fact
providing humanitarian assistance from its own nations.
</P>
<P>
Senafe, a border town of Eritrea, has been under control of
Ethiopian army since a new round of border conflict broke out in
mid-May between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Instead of attacking on Eritrean civilians, Ethiopian army is "
distributing fertilizer inputs and agricultural implements to
enable the farmers in the area to make the best use of the rainy
season and plough their plots", the office said.
</P>
<P>
While accusing the Eritrean side of refusing a planned United
Nations team visit, which was to undertake humanitarian missions
in the Senafe area, the office said that Ethiopia agreed that the
humanitarian situation in Senafe area be addressed within the
framework of the mission of the U.N. reconnaissance team to
Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
The office also appealed to the international community to
exert enough pressure on the Eritrean authorities to
unconditionally release the thousands of Ethiopian citizens taken
in captivity and held in very hostile and inhabitable camps.
</P>
</TEXT>
