<HEADLINE> S. Africa Supports Palestinians to Declare Statehood: Mbeki </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 3 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Thabo Mbeki said on Thursday that his government supports the
Palestinian Authority to declare an independent Palestinian state
on September 13.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint news conference in Pretoria after meeting
with Mbeki, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat reiterated that
September 13 is the last possible date for independence.
</P>
<P>
"On that date we have the right to declare an independent state,
" Arafat said. "I'm still committed to the hope that we still may
conclude the peace process by September 13 through the help of U.S.
President Bill Clinton."
</P>
<P>
He said the main obstacles to reaching a final peace agreement
are Palestinians' right to get back East Jerusalem, as well as the
right of Palestinian refugees to return or get compensation.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Israeli troops have been deployed in many areas of the
Palestinian territories, Arafat said. "This is a real menace to
the peace process and our future. We have conveyed this to the
Americans and our friends."
</P>
<P>
Mbeki said: "We hope Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
recognizes the flexibility shown by the Palestinian leadership to
find solutions to address all the concerns."
</P>
<P>
He noted that South Africa's support for Palestinian statehood
is a long-standing policy, which is also the policy of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) and the Non-Aligned Movement (
NAM).
</P>
<P>
The meeting between the two leaders followed Arafat's five-day
visit to France and several Arab states in the wake of the failed
U.S.-brokered peace negotiations between him and Barak at Camp
David.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said the Palestinians need South Africa's help, both as
a country and as chair of NAM.
</P>
<P>
He added he has again mentioned to Mbeki that he wants former
South African President Nelson Mandela to act as international
mediator in the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
