<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's post and
telecommunications workers Thursday vowed to continue a
countrywide strike over pay cut which entered the fourth day.
</P>
<P>
The workers went on strike on Monday following the decision by
the management to reduce their salaries by up to 56 percent.
</P>
<P>
President of Zimbabwe Post and Telecommunications Workers'
Union Lovemore Matombo told the Zimbabwe News Agency that the
management had infringed the rights of the workers.
</P>
<P>
"We had not yet concluded our negotiations and all of a sudden
the management unilaterally decided to cut our salaries," he said.
</P>
<P>
The workers were awarded salary increments of up to 300 percent
last February.
</P>
<P>
Matombo dismissed claims by the management that the strike was
illegal, saying what was illegal instead was the action by the
management to reduce salaries without consulting the workers.
</P>
<P>
The strike has paralyzed postal and telecommunication services
countrywide. 
