<HEADLINE> Mandela Ready to Help Solve Palestinian Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Former South African
President Nelson Mandela said on Thursday that he was prepared to
do everything possible to help find a peaceful solution to the
Palestinian issue.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his home in Johannesburg after talks with visiting
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, Mandela confirmed that the
Palestinian leader had asked him to act as a mediator in the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Mandela called for collective effort involving the West and
other Arab states to solve the Palestinian issue, saying he could
not bring about a solution on his own.
</P>
<P>
He said the reason why the U.S.-brokered Camp David talks
between Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak last month
had failed was that it had not been a collective process.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said he had warned U.S. President Bill Clinton in
October last year that peace in the Middle East had not been
brokered for 25 years because nations had failed to act
collectively.
</P>
<P>
He said it was important that countries like the U.S., Britain,
France, Egypt, Saudi Arabia and Russia worked together to broker
peace.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said he would phone the heads of states of these
countries in an attempt to revive the peace process. 
</P>
