<HEADLINE> Burundian President in S. Africa for Talks With Mandela </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Burundian President Pierre
Buyoya arrived in South Africa on Thursday for talks with former
President Nelson Mandela in a bid to break a deadlock in peace
efforts in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
Buyoya was scheduled to hold talks later Thursday with Mandela,
who has been trying to broker a peace plan aimed at ending a seven-
year civil war in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
The Burundian government and opposition leaders have been at
loggerheads over the release of political prisoners, the
announcement of a cease-fire and problems related to the
implementation of a proposed accord.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the proposed peace plan has been scheduled for
August 28.
</P>
<P>
Buyoya, however, wanted hostilities to cease before the 109-page
accord could be signed. Mandela expressed the belief that this
could follow the signing. Mandela has also proposed that a
transitional government be set up, Hutu anti-government forces be
integrated into the Tutsi-dominated army and political prisoners
be released.
</P>
<P>
The conflict erupted in October 1993 when the country's first
democratically elected president Melchior Ndadaye, a Hutu, was
assassinated by Tutsi troops. At least 200,000 people, most of
them civilians, have been killed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
