<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EAC Countries See Imports Twice Exports in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The value of goods imported
by East African Community (EAC) countries in 1998 was over twice
the value of their exports in the same period.
</P>
<P>
According to an economic report issued Thursday by the EAC
secretariat based in Tanzania's northern town of Arusha, its three
member countries, namely Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda, exported a
total of 3.05 billion U.S. dollars worth of goods in 1998, while
imported goods worth 6.18 billion dollars in the same year.
</P>
<P>
The principal exports included tea, horticulture, coffee,
cement, cotton, tobacco and diamond. Others were fish and fish
products, soda ash, gemstones, limestone and gold.
</P>
<P>
As far as imports were concerned, the report said, the major
products included machinery, industrial supplies, motor vehicles
and chassis parts and accessories, and refined petroleum products.
</P>
<P>
As for tourism, the three countries under review received a
total of 1.6 million tourists compared to 1.2 million in 1993. The
industry brought them an income of 948 million dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the total foreign debt for them amounted to 703
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Presidents of Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda signed in Arusha last
November the East African Community Treaty, which is aimed at
gradually forging the block into a monetary union and later a
political federation.
</P>
<P>
The regional block, with a combined area of 1.8 million
kilometers and a combined population of 80 million, hopes to
exploit economies of scale and develop a regional economic master-
plan to stimulate investment, notably in transport and
communications networks, power generation and the manufacturing
industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
