<HEADLINE> S. Africa Faces Difficult Task of Alleviating Poverty: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He said South Africa still lags behind most other middle income
countries in key human development indicators such as life
expectancy, infant mortality and adult literacy.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the launch of this year's United Nations Human
Development report in Johannesburg, Skweyiya said statistics on
South Africa did not present the full picture of the human
suffering experienced in communities on the margins of a society.
</P>
<P>
"South Africa, as we all know is characterized by persistent
and deepening poverty, which is accompanied by social alienation
and related pathologies," he said.
</P>
<P>
The poorest 40 percent of households received only 11 percent
of the country's total income, while the richest 10 percent
received more than 40 percent, according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
The age, gender and racial characteristics of the population
indicated that the most vulnerable households were in the rural,
peri-urban and township areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The realities ... demand that we seriously find ways of
turning the rhetoric of democratic governance and human rights
into concrete action as a world community," Skweyiya said.
</P>
<P>
"Let us remember that beyond the confines of these cloisters
are real people with real and urgent need," he said. 
</P>
