<HEADLINE> Another Burundian Rebel Group Refuses to Sign Peace Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Another main Hutu rebel
group in Burundi has declared that it will not sign the peace
accord scheduled for later this month, the independent Guardian
newspaper in Tanzania reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Bihute Bernard, spokesman of the Hutu People's Liberation Party-
-the National Liberation Force (PALIPEHUTU-FNL) in East Africa,
was quoted as saying in Tanzanian capital on Wednesday that his
party has nothing to do with the anticipated signing of the said
peace accord, therefore they will not sign it.
</P>
<P>
"How can we take part in a deal in which we were not involved
since it started about four years ago? " the spokesman asked.
</P>
<P>
Bernard said his group was ready to take part in the talks from
the beginning, but some personalities inside the mediation team
became hurdles to its participation.
</P>
<P>
He said the accord would be meaningful if the group, under
Commandant Kabura Cossana, held talks with President Pierre Buyoya
's government.
</P>
<P>
The talks would be on the merger of "our armies," he said. "
This is the only way we can end the 7-year-old war. Otherwise, let
them sign but the war will continue," he asserted.
</P>
<P>
The group is the third party to declare that it will not sign
the accord.
</P>
<P>
Last week, another major armed rebel group CNND-FDD (the
National Council for the Defense of Democracy --Forces for the
Defense of Democracy) and the military government under President
Pierre Buyoya said they will not sign the accord, which is being
discussed by warring parties involved in the peace talks held in
Tanzania's northern town of Arusha.
</P>
<P>
Despite efforts made by peace facilitator, former South African
President Nelson Mandela, PALIPEHUTU-FNL did not attend the last
round of peace talks held two weeks ago in Arusha, which brought
together 19 parties and groups involved in the peace process and
CNDD-FDD which attended for the first time as an observer.
</P>
<P>
Mandela had announced earlier last month that a peace deal
would be signed on July 20. However, the date was later postponed
to August 28 because of "some material details" related to a
ceasefire and the implementation of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Under the power-sharing draft accord, the Tutsi minority, which
has dominated Burundi's political and economic life since
independence, would have to hand over power to a democratically
elected government in three years' time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
