<HEADLINE> Canadian Company to Try AIDS Drug in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- A Canadian HIV/AIDS company has
chosen Zambia to try its Anti Retro Viral Drugs, the Post
newspaper reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Nehe Nwankwo, HIV-VAC Inc.'s representative in Zambia, said the
company, which has its liaison office in Nodola, Copperbelt
Province of Zambia, is awaiting a response from the Zambian
government.
</P>
<P>
Nwankwo was quoted as saying that if approved the drugs will
bring down the rates of HIV/AIDS infections in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The vaccine which was originally discovered by Professor
Skinner of Birmingham University in Britain was meant for trials
before any nation could approve it.
</P>
<P>
He said the Anti Retro Viral Drugs which is already on trials
in Russia is used in three phases.
</P>
<P>
Nwankwo explained that the vaccine should be first tested for
its safety, then its efficacy and finally if it can really prevent
the HIV/AIDS infection.
</P>
<P>
He said for the whole program to succeed, there was a need to
educate the public on the benefits, risks and ethical issues
concerning the vaccine and those on trial.
</P>
<P>
Nwankwo assured the nation that if approved, the vaccine will
be free and those on trial will be supported fully until the
vaccine is approved. 
</P>
