<P>
The newspaper quoted officials from Zambia Intelligence
Security Services (ZISS) as saying that Mwila would soon be picked
up and detained on allegations that he is planning to unlawfully
topple President Frederick Chiluba's government.
</P>
<P>
"It's possible there could be a declaration of a state of
emergency so that even Mwila's supporters are all picked up and
detained," said the officials, adding, "All this is aimed at
totally frustrating his presidential ambitions."
</P>
<P>
Mwila was quoted as saying that he has heard something like
that and is ready for anything.
</P>
<P>
He said that getting rid of him would not solve the problems
Chiluba and his ruling party are facing, adding that time would
vindicate him because he is not a violent man by nature.
</P>
<P>
Mwila lost his ministerial portfolio in early July days after
he was expelled from the country's ruling Movement for Multi-Party
Democracy (MMD) on a charge of involvement in anti-party
activities.
</P>
<P>
Mwila announced his candidature for the MMD presidency last May
in a bid to run for the country's presidency in the general
elections to be held next year.
</P>
<P>
Mwila, one of the country's richest magnates, helped incumbent
President Chiluba defeat former president Kenneth Kaunda in the
1991 elections. He is seen as one of the leading candidates to
replace Chiluba in the next year's elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
