<HEADLINE> Kenya Rehabilitates International Airport in Nairobi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The Jomo Kenyatta International
Airport in Kenya's capital Nairobi is undergoing rehabilitation to
cater for passenger movement ranging between 2.5 million and 2.7
million annually, according to the Kenya Airports Authority (KAA).
</P>
<P>
KAA Managing Director Stephen Muriithi Wednesday said in a
statement that the airport has recorded unprecedented traffic and
passenger growth, leading to a saturation capacity at the terminal
building, the East African Standard newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Further traffic growth will result in considerable congestion
in transit lounges and check-in counter among other facilities,"
Muriithi added.
</P>
<P>
A Belgian company, L M Chapeaux, won the bid to undertaken the
rehabilitation project at a contract sum of 2.6 billion shillings
(about 34.8 million U.S. dollars), said Muriithi, adding that the
company provided the authority with more flexible sourcing and
procurement for equipment from various countries such as Britain,
the Netherlands, Germany and Belgium.
</P>
<P>
To facilitate the development of the airport as a hub, Muriithi
said, there is need for all constraints to traffic growth to be
eliminated and facilities be refurbished to meet set standards in
safety, security, operational efficiency and passenger comfort.
</P>
<P>
The managing director said between 1990 and 1997, passenger
traffic using the airport grew at an average rate of 5 percent
annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
