<HEADLINE> World Bank Resumes Loan to Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has approved a
loan of 150 million U.S. dollars to Kenya in recognition of the
country's reform efforts last year, according to a World Bank
official.
</P>
<P>
The new loan would be released in three portions of 50 million
dollars each in the next nine months and the first portion was
available immediately, Kenya's Daily Nation newspaper Thursday
quoted the bank's country director to Kenya Harold Wackman as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank suspended its budgetary support to Kenya in 1997
soon after the International Monetary Fund (IMF) halted its loan,
citing corruption and mismanagement in the government.
</P>
<P>
The other two portions of the loan approved on Wednesday would
be given when Kenya meets specific performance targets, Wackman
said.
</P>
<P>
The loan is to support poverty reduction, retrenchment in civil
service, privatization of state-owned enterprises and budget
support, according to Wackman.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kenyan Finance Minister Chris Okemo said
negotiations with the bank for a 75-million-dollar power emergency
loan were progressing. The sum of money will be used to buy an
emergency power generator to alleviate the current severe power
shortage.
</P>
<P>
The IMF resumed its loan to Kenya last Thursday, saying that
the east African country had made a clear improvement in anti-
corruption.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's economy has been in the doldrums since 1997 when most
international financial institutions withdrew aids from the
country. The economic growth declined to 1.4 percent in 1999 from
4.3 percent in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
