<HEADLINE> Kenya to Publish New Petroleum Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has drafted
a new petroleum bill containing tough penalties against those
violating rules governing the sale of petroleum products in a
liberalized market.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Energy Minister Francis Masakhalia disclosed here
Wednesday that the new bill has covered key areas not included in
the existing legislation while fines and penalties have been
enhanced, the East African Standard newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said his ministry had finalized the draft on petroleum bill
which has been forwarded to the Attorney-General to be enacted
into an Act of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that the new law will address the issues of
adulterated fuel products in a liberalized market, and the
existence of sub-standard retail outlets.
</P>
<P>
The bill requires all petroleum facilities to carry out an
environmental impact assessment of their undertaking, indicating
possible hazards emanating from their operations, Masakhalia said,
adding environment polluters and local authorities are required to
designate parking places for petroleum road tankers.
</P>
<P>
Under the new legislation, he said, companies will also be
required to report to the ministry all significant accidents which
may occur during their operations.
</P>
<P>
"Failure to comply with these provisions will attract
substantial fines," the minister warned, saying the new bill has
been enacted over failure by the current law to address some of
the problems in the petroleum sub-sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
