<HEADLINE> Kenyan Herdsmen Told to Be out of National Parks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Kenya Wildlife Service (KWS) has
told drought-striken pastoralists to drive their livestock out of
Mount Kenya National Park, saying that the herdsmen were an
additional threat to the forest park.
</P>
<P>
Herdsmen were aggravating the menace to the park posed by
illegal timber merchants and bhang-growers, Kenya's major
newspaper Daily Nation Thursday quoted KWS director Nehemiah
Rotich as saying.
</P>
<P>
"If they are allowed into Mount Kenya, it will create the
impression that it is all right for other drought-striken herdsmen
to move in Amboseli and Tsavo national parks," Rotich said.
</P>
<P>
Mount Kenya National Park, situated near the Equator, abounds
in a wide variety of plants and animals of temperate and cold
zones. The park is one of natural treasures designated by the
United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's national parks, with its unique plants and wild animals,
allure many foreign visitors to the country. The tourism sector is
the third biggest foreign currency earner after coffee and tea.
</P>
<P>
Rotich also urged local officials to help keeping the herdsmen
out to the park, saying tourists do not come to see cattle.
</P>
<P>
However, the failure of last two consecutive rainy seasons has
led to a severe drought, which is pushing Kenyan pastoralists to
the brink of starvation. Livestock have died in large numbers due
to lack of pasture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
