<HEADLINE> Zambia Reduces Communities' Education Contributions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has reduced
communities' contributions to education under the Micro Projects
Unit (MPU) from 25 percent to 15 percent, Zambia Daily Mail
reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Education Minister Godfrey Miyanda was quoted as saying to the
parliament on Wednesday that, the decision to cut contributions to
the construction, upgrading and rehabilitation of schools followed
complaints from lawmakers and the general public that some
communities were failing to raise the 25 percent contribution
under the old MPU arrangement.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the minister said that the previous administrative
cost of 1.5 million kwacha (about 500 U.S. dollars), which was
demanded by MPU, is no longer a requirement for the disbursement
of funds.
</P>
<P>
He said since November 1999 his ministry has released about 4.5
million dollars to MPU for disbursement to projects throughout the
country.
</P>
<P>
About 6,000 classrooms will be built and 2,000 will be
rehabilitated between 1999 to 2005 and 2,000 teachers' houses will
be built within the same period, the minister said. 
</P>
