<HEADLINE> L. American Economy To Grow 4 Pct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The economy in Latin America and
the Caribbean will record this year a 4 percent economic growth
and a 10 percent inflation, the Economic Commission for Latin
America and the Caribbean (CEPAL) forecast Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Latin America and the Caribbean are gradually recovering this
year from the recession that affected many economies of the region
in the second half of 1998, said the CEPAL in a report.
</P>
<P>
The organization, with its headquarters in Santiago, said that
the 10 percent average inflation of the region will be similar to
that in the 1997-1999 period, and that there will be a slight
recovery in the labor markets.
</P>
<P>
The CEPAL foresees in the study a current account deficit for
this year close to 3 percent of the gross domestic product, a
percentage that does not mean a major variance from 1999, but that
is much less than that of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Latin America and the Caribbean have started a new cycle of
growth in the last 10 years at a bigger rate than that in the
previous years, and from a global point of view, added the CEPAL.
</P>
</TEXT>
