<HEADLINE> Italy Calls For Turkey Tighter Anti-immigration Controls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Italy renewed its call on Tuesday
for Turkey to keep a closer eye on its ports, in the wake of the
arrival on the Italian southern coast of Calabria of an immigrant-
laden ship of Turkish origins.
</P>
<P>
The Italian Foreign Ministry sent for Ankara's Ambassador to
Rome Necati Utcan to inform him of Italy's "great concern" over
the incident of the ship, the Kalsit, which ran aground near
Crotone on the Calabrian coast early last Sunday morning with 418
illegal immigrants aboard, Italian news agency Ansa reported.
</P>
<P>
Italian Foreign Ministry Secretary General Umberto Vattani told
Utcan that Rome "hoped that the Turkish authorities would show the
greatest vigilance in order to prevent similar episodes recurring.
"
</P>
<P>
Vattani stressed the importance of close bilateral co-operation
on illegal immigration issues, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
It said that Utcan had underscored Turkey's awareness of the
seriousness of the problem and its willingness to collaborate
fully with Italy and other neighboring countries in order to
combat criminal activities such as immigrant smuggling.
</P>
<P>
Utcan also told Vattani that the Turkish authorities were eager
to glean as much information as possible about the Kalsit and its
itinerary, in order to track down those responsible for any lax
monitoring.
</P>
<P>
Illegal immigration has become a burning social and political
issue in Italy, particularly in the wake of a fatal incident on
July 24,when four people, including two Italian police officers,
were killed when immigrant traffickers in a high- powered rubber
dinghy rammed a coast guard boat just off the coast of Puglia
region.
</P>
<P>
The incident caused a huge public outcry and Opposition demands
that the government take a firmer line against smugglers and those
countries from which the traffickers set out. 
</P>
